<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 21 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic
briefs from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- For the first time, Egypt will take part in Tehran
International Trade and Industrial Fair, which is due to be held
in October, Cairo-based Arabic newspaper Al-Shaab reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
On its part, Iran will participate in the Cairo International
Trade fair in March 2000.
</P>
<P>
The mutual participation by the two Muslim states in their
fairs comes within the framework of a number of steps taken by
Cairo and Tehran to promote bilateral ties and confidence
building, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- South Korea delivered on Tuesday the newly-built
Iran-Sousangerd oil tanker to representatives of the national oil
tanker company.
</P>
<P>
Iranian Ambassador to Seoul Mohsen Talaei said that the
158,000-ton tanker is to leave South Korean waters for Persian
Gulf on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Iran-Sousangerd is the first oil tanker built by the Daewoo
conglomerate for Iran under its latest contract with the country.
</P>
<P>
The building cost of the oil tanker with a capacity of carrying
1.2 million barrels of crude, is financed by the South Korean
banks and will be paid back from its revenues in the long run.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran and Austria inked on Tuesday six agreements and
memoranda of understanding in cultural, industrial, investment and
health care fields.
</P>
<P>
The agreements were signed in the presence of President
Mohammad Khatami and his Austrian counterpart Thomas Klestil, who
is in Tehran on a two-day visit, accompanied by a 80-member
Austrian businessmen delegation.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- U.S. energy giant Enron Corp. will purchase
480,000 tons per annum (tpa) of liquefied natural gas (LNG) from
Abu Dhabi Gas Liquefaction Co. (Adgas) of the United Arab Emirates
for 20 years.
</P>
<P>
The LNG will be used as feedstock for Enron Corp.'s upcoming
power plant in the western Indian state of Maharashtra, said the
Gulf News daily on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"Our affiliate in India, the Dabhol Power Co. (DPC), has
completed an agreement with Adgas to purchase 480,000 tpa of
LNG. The deal is for a 20 year period and deliveries will
commence from the last quarter of 2001," Kelly Kimberly, senior
director of international public relations of Enron Corp. was
quoted as saying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
