<HEADLINE> U.S. Warns Pakistani Military against Stepping in Politics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 21 (Xinhua) -- The Clinton administration
has quietly warned the Pakistani military not to involve itself in
politics because of its outrage over the government's handling of
the kashmir crisis this past summer, U.S. officials said on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
the officials said signs of potential instability in Pakistan
have prompted the Clinton administration to reaffirm its support
for the government headed by Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan's military leaders were indignant at Sharif's promise
to U.S. President Bill Clinton to withdraw Pakistani troops at the
height of the crisis with India this past summer over Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the military discontent, opposition parties,
which have formed a grand alliance, are also holding relentless
protests against Sharif.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. officials said that the Clinton administration had
made the warning to the Pakistani military to fend off any threat
of subversion of the current Pakistani government.
</P>
<P>
Sharif has said that the opposition war trying to destabilize
his government rather than wait for the next round of elections in
2001. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
