<HEADLINE> Ghana Calls on U.S. to Reconsider Ties With Cuba </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Ghana Tuesday urged
the United States to reconsider its relations with Cuba, urging
Washington to engage "constructive dialogue with the Cuban
Government."
</P>
<P>
The statement came as Ghanaian President Jerry Rawlings took
the floor at the general debate of the 54th General Assembly
session, which began Monday and will last two weeks.
</P>
<P>
"Following the U.S. government's recent sensitivity to the
concerns of the international community, Ghana would like to urge
it to seriously consider the resumption of indirect relations with
Cuba," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We are convinced that such contacts would yield desired
results especially if they take place in the context of
constructive dialogue with the Cuban Government," he said.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated his "concern over the continued non-compliance
with key United Nations resolutions which call for an end to the
commercial and financial embargo against Cuba."
</P>
<P>
"It is our sincere conviction that the economic blockade of
three decades and more vintage against Cuba and the Helms-Burton
and D'Amato legislation are a breach of international law and a
violation of the principles of the United Nations Charter," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Washington suspended its relations with Cuba on January 3,
1961, and the Clinton administration continued blockade and
embargo against Cuba despite the international community called
for the lifting of the unilateral measures against the island
country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
