<HEADLINE> Iran Praises Iranian-Russian Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Minister of Higher
Education Mostafa Moin said Tuesday that a science and technology
agreement signed between Iran and Russia mark a turning point in
the strategic bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
He said that "the important agreement was signed only one day
after the limitations announced by the U.S. on Iran-Russia
cooperation," the Iranian official Islamic Republic News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
Russia has long been accused by the U.S. and Israel in
particular of helping Iran develop its nuclear weapons program by
training students, building a nuclear power plant in southern Iran
and providing missile technology.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the U.S. banned aid to seven Russian research and
manufacturing enterprises found to have sold sensitive weapons
technology to such countries as Iran, Libya and North Korea.
</P>
<P>
Moin said the agreement calls for bilateral cooperation in new
advanced fields of training, research and technology, material
science, energy, Caspian Sea environment and resources, refining
oil derivatives, information technology and genetic engineering.
</P>
<P>
The agreement will usher in new era in bilateral scientific
cooperation, Moin said, adding that "raising the attendance of
Iranian students with scholarship in Russian university is also
envisioned in the agreement."
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that the country will benefit from such
agreements by standing firmly against the hurried and aggressive
limitations imposed by the U.S. on Iran-Russia cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The agreement has been ratified by Iranian cabinet and Russian
government and the lower house Duma, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
