<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Northern Irish Feuding Leaders Hold Face-to-Face Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Chaired by U.S. mediator
George Mitchell, Norther Ireland's feuding Protestant and Roman
Catholice politicians held crucial face-to-face talks on Tuesday
to review the problems plaguing the historic Good Friday
agreement.
</P>
<P>
The talks, held in the province's capital Belfast, were the
first round-table session as part of Mitchell's review, which he
launched three weeks ago at the invitation of the British and
Irish governments.
</P>
<P>
Ulster Unionist Party (UUP) leader David Trimble, and Sinn Fein
leader Gerry Adams, brought together by Mitchell, attended the
talks aimed at overcoming weeks of deadlock.
</P>
<P>
At the start of the talks, Adams and Trimble, disputed over the
creation of a coalition provincial government and guerrilla
disarmament, challenged each other's commitment to the agreement
signed in April last year.
</P>
<P>
Adams said his movement, which has accused Trimble's UUP of
footdragging, doubted the unionists had the "political will" to
implement the agreement.
</P>
<P>
But Trimble insisted that it was up to Sinn Fein, the political
wing of the Irish Republican Army, to honor its commitments.
</P>
<P>
It was the first top level meeting of delegations between the
parties since abortive talks chaired by British and Irish prime
ministers in July.
</P>
<P>
Mitchell's officials played down any prospect of an early
breakthrough and said the former senator, who has met the parties
individually, has not tabled new proposals.
</P>
<P>
UUP and Sinn Fein spokesmen said they were approaching
Tuesday's meeting in a positive frame of mind.
</P>
<P>
Trimble said unionists were prepared to give republicans "time
and space" to meet their commitments.
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein insists it is striving for disarmament but cannot
force the IRA to hand in guns. It accuses unionists of blocking
the accord's implementation at every turn.
</P>
<P>
"There is no formula (to end the stalemate) on the table at
this stage," said a spokesman for Mitchell. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
