<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Currency to Devalue: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 21 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwean dollar is
forecast to fall by more than 30 percent against the U.S. dollar
before the end of the year in the wake of speculation that the
government is under pressure to allow the currency to float.
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwe News Agency Tuesday quoted analysts as saying that
the local currency would be trading at between 48 and 50 to the
greenback by December this year.
</P>
<P>
The forecast comes in the speculation on the foreign currency
market in the wake of the pressure on the government by the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) to allow market forces to
determine the level of the Zimbabwean dollar.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in January this year, the Bankers' Association of
Zimbabwe introduced informal currency controls, which have kept
the Zimbabwean dollar at 38.15 against the U.S. dollar since
March.
</P>
<P>
The free trading of the Zimbabwean dollar was one of the
conditions in the government's letter of intent to the IMF, said
the association.
</P>
<P>
According to the new agreement agreed between the Zimbabwean
government and the IMF, the latter will provide 193 million U.S
dollars stand-by support to Zimbabwe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
