<DOCNO> XIE19990922.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Current Account Balance Goes Back into </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 21 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's current
account balance plunged 3.4 billion rand (about 557 million U.S.
dollars) in the second quarter ending in June due mainly to lower
merchandise exports.
</P>
<P>
It was a reversal of a 4.9 billion-rand (800 million dollars)
surplus in the first three months of the year, according to the
seasonally adjusted and annualized data released by the South
African Reserve Bank in Johannesburg Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the balance of payments on current account, the
bank stated: "The major part of the deterioration -- approximately
four-fifths of the absolute change in the current account balance
-- was due to a decline in exports."
</P>
<P>
The central bank revealed in its latest quarterly bulletin that
 merchandise exports had fallen from 148.4 billion rand (24.3
billion dollars) in the March quarter to 141.5 billion rand (23.1
billion dollars) by June 30.
</P>
<P>
Net gold exports were down over the same period from 24.7
billion rand (4.02 billion dollars) to 23.8 billion rand (3.9
billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
The bank said the volume of merchandise imports increased by
about one percent in the second quarter. These imports were mainly
manufacturing equipment which augured well for faster domestic
demand growth.
</P>
<P>
The merchandise imports rose from 142.9 billion rand (23.4
billion dollars) in the previous quarter to 143.7 billion rand
(23.6 billion dollars) in the June quarter.
</P>
<P>
The 557-million-dollar deficit was however a far cry from the
third and fourth quarters of 1998 when deficits of 19.8 billion
rand (3.2 billion dollars) and 18.5 billion rand (3 billion
dollars) respectively were recorded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
