<HEADLINE> Soil Erosion Endangers Ethiopian Fertile Land: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopia has encountered
an increasing expansion of soil erosion, which will bring about
degradation upon the productive lands, Italian scholar Paolo Billi
said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Billi, professor of Ferrara University of Italy, said in a
lecture that much of the fertile land of Ethiopia has currently
been washed away by soil erosion.
</P>
<P>
The professor attributed the extensive soil erosion mainly to
the wide- range of deforestation over the last few decades,
climatic change and mismanagement of the soil.
</P>
<P>
Some parts of Ethiopia would be endangered of desertification,
which in turn could aggravate soil erosion, he said.
</P>
<P>
The initial gully could develop its volume by 25 percent in a
single rains season, he said, "The situation unfortunately remains
irreversible once developed into a higher extent."
</P>
<P>
The professor stressed the need to further enhance
afforestation and irrigation development to address the growing
threat of soil erosion in the country.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, owing to soil erosion and
increasing population, the average land holding of Ethiopian
farmers have decreased from 1.8 hectares in 1988 to 0.8 hectares
in 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
