<DOCNO> XIE19990922.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton: Responsibility Be Shared for Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Amid debate over how
to respond to humanitarian crisis, U.S. President Bill Clinton
said here Tuesday that the responsibility should be shared for
preventing or stopping such kind of catastrophes.
</P>
<P>
Addressing world leaders at the general debate of the U.N.
General Assembly, the president said that to strengthen the
capacity of the international community to prevent and stop the
outbreaks of mass killing and displacement "will require a shared
responsibility."
</P>
<P>
"I know some are troubled that the United States and others
cannot respond to every humanitarian catastrophe in the world. We
cannot do everything, everywhere," said Clinton, who flew here
from Washington D.C. early this morning.
</P>
<P>
He was responding to a call made by U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan Monday for prompt humanitarian intervention where ever crisis
occurs. The New York Times said Monday the United States should be
blamed for the failure to halt massacre in Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
The Americans prefer to let such regional organizations as NATO
and the organization of African Unity play a greater part in
quelling ethnic violence and regional conflicts. The
conservative-dominant Congress has limited the administration's
capability to intervene in places of trouble by cutting its
spending in the past few years.
</P>
<P>
However, the United States led the NATO allied force earlier
this year in extensive bombardment of Yugoslavia in the wake of
Kosovo crisis. The military operations, without authorization from
the Security Council, have challenged the status of the U.N. and
triggered off heated debate on how to respond to humanitarian
crisis.
</P>
<P>
"Had we chosen to do nothing in the face of this brutality, I
don't believe we would have strengthened the U.N. We would have
risked discrediting the U.N.," said President Clinton in defense
of the NATO military intervention against criticism from some
countries including Russia and China.
</P>
<P>
The critics complained that the U.S.-led NATO military
operation has set a "dangerous precedence" in the U.N. history by
using force against a sovereign state without authorization from
the Security Council.
</P>
<P>
Clinton argued that the response in every case should not be
the same, believing that either collective military force, or
concerted economic and political pressure combined with diplomacy
could be chosen under different circumstances and depending on
national interests.
</P>
<P>
He made no direct reference to the ongoing debate over whether
human rights should precede state sovereignty. However, he made
humanitarian intervention one of his three themes addressed at the
U.N. Assembly.
</P>
<P>
The president firstly urged for an unrelenting battle against
extreme poverty and for shared prosperity so that no part of
humanity is left behind in the global economy.
</P>
<P>
He said he would push for the development of new vaccines to
narrow the gap in health between the rich and poor countries.
</P>
<P>
On weapons proliferation, Clinton vowed to continue to contain
Iraqi President Saddam Hussein, while warning against the fall of
deadly weapons into the hands of terrorist groups.
</P>
<P>
"We must continue to ease the suffering of the Iraqi people. At
the same time, we cannot allow Saddam (Hussein) to flout 40
successive U.N. Security Council resolutions and rebuild his
arsenal," the president said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton agreed that the U.N. was indispensable in meeting the
challenges facing the international community, pledging to
continue his fight with Congress over the U.S. 1.3 billion U.S.
dollar arrears to the U.N..Congress has linked the payment to
abortion and reduced contribution rates.
</P>
<P>
"It is precisely because we are committed to the U.N. that we
believe it must be managed effectively. But we also have a
responsibility to equip the U.N. with the resources it needs to be
effective," the president said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
