<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 2 Pro-Israeli Militiamen Killed in South Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Two members of the
pro-Israeli South Lebanon Army (SLA) were killed in south Lebanon
Tuesday morning, Lebanese security sources said.
</P>
<P>
The casualties occurred when a SLA outpost in the central
section of the Israeli occupied border zone in south Lebanon was
hit by Lebanese guerrillas' mortar and rocket attacks.
</P>
<P>
A SLA member was killed instantly and another died of wounds in
hospital.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon's two Muslim Shiite military groups Hezbollah and Amal
claimed their fighters launched offensives against several Israeli
and SLA positions inside the zone, causing direct casualties.
</P>
<P>
In Jerusalem, Israeli army confirmed the casualties, adding
Israeli warplanes blasted suspected targets of Lebanese guerrillas
in Iqlim Toufah area on the edge of the border enclave as a
retaliation.
</P>
<P>
The fresh fatalities raised to 16 the number of the SLA
members killed in south Lebanon since the start of this year
while 13 Israeli soldiers lost their lives.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a self-declared security zone in south Lebanon in
1985 with a claimed aim of protecting its north from Lebanese
guerrillas' cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
Since then, Lebanon's resistance movement spearheaded by the
Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God, has been fighting to
oust Israeli troops and the SLA out of the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
