<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 16:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Rejects Bigger U.N. Role in Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Israel rejected on Tuesday
the United Nations' intention to play a more active political role
in the Middle East peace process, defining the world body can only
look after economic matters in the region.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, the Israeli Foreign Ministry said "the basis of
the Arab-Israeli peace process since its advent with the 1991
Madrid Peace Conference has been direct, face-to-face negotiations
between the parties."
</P>
<P>
"And any attempts to alter these terms of reference, including
the involvement of the United Nations in the negotiating process,
are unacceptable to the government of Israel," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Ministry issued this statement after learning that
Terje Roed-Larsen of Norway, who helped oversee secret talks that
led to the Oslo accords, will be appointed as U.N. special
coordinator for the Middle East peace process. U.N. Secretary
General Kofi Annan disclosed this in a letter in New York Monday.
</P>
<P>
Roed-Larsen is also named Annan's personal representative to
the Palestinian Liberation Organization and the Palestinian
National Authority. He is to replace Indian diplomat Chinmaya
Gharekhan.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry's statement clearly indicated that Israel will
not allow the U.N. to play the role in the process beyond the
economic areas.
</P>
<P>
Israel has repeatedly clarified to the U.N. and its
representatives that it can not accept an expansion of the title,
mandate and powers of the outgoing U.N. special coordinator,
Chinmaya Gharekhan, beyond the economic functional areas, to which
he was charged.
</P>
<P>
Gharekhan will leave his post on September 30 as U.N. special
representative to multilateral talks on Middle East Peace and as
U.N. special coordinator in the occupied territories.
</P>
<P>
Roed-Larsen will take up his new post on October 1.
</P>
<P>
Annan said in his letter that Roed-Larsen will have the task of
making appropriate preparations within the U.N. for enhancing its
development assistance in support of the peace process and
represent him in discussions with the parties and the
international community in all matters related to continuing
United Nations support to the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Reod-Larsen's base of operations will remain in Gaza, Annan
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990922.0020 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Joint Efforts to Curb Angola-Namibia Border Crimes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, September 21 (Xinhua) -- A senior Angolan official
Tuesday called for the Angola-Namibia union of defense and
security forces in joint actions against the organized crime along
the common frontier.
</P>
<P>
Vice Defense Minister General Demosthenes Amos Chilingutila
made the call here at the opening ceremony of a meeting of Angolan
and Namibian experts on defense and security before the sixth
ministerial session of a mixed commission scheduled for Friday.
</P>
<P>
"The necessary cooperation in combating the organized crime in
the two countries and the actions of the people loyal to (Jonas)
Savimbi, either in Angola or in north Namibia, concretely in the
Caprivi Strip, deserves an immediate response from the Namibian
defense and security forces," said the Angolan official.
</P>
<P>
Chilingutila, head of the Angolan delegation for the bilateral
meeting, pointed out that the rebels of the National Union for
Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) led by Jonas Savimbi had
taken advantage of the period posterior to the signature of the
1994 Lusaka peace accord for rearming themselves, recruiting new
soldiers, training them and organizing them in new units.
</P>
<P>
The rebel movement UNITA has controled over some rural areas
and the east and southeast frontier.
</P>
<P>
During a battle against the separatist militants in the
northeast Caprivi Strip in early August this year, the Namibian
government captured and then expelled seven UNITA members.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the Namibian separatists smashed by the
government troops have fled into south Angola and Zambia.
</P>
<P>
The Angolan government made a quick response to the incident by
saying that it will help capture the Namibian rebels.
</P>
<P>
At the fifth session of the mixed commission on September 24,
1998, Angola and Namibia signed a protocol on cooperation in
security and defense, in a bid to reinforce the security of the
common frontier, crack down on the robberies of cars and animals
and fight against the organized criminals.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
