<HEADLINE> Thai Exports in First Seven Months Rise 7.8 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's exports in the
first seven months of this year increased 7.8 percent from the
same period last year to 32.2 billion U.S. dollars, a Government
House press release said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Export volume increased 7.8 percent in the first seven months
of this year, while the value dropped 5.3 percent due to the
decline in the prices of agricultural and agro-industrial products
including rice, rubber, tapioca, frozen and canned seafood and
cane sugar.
</P>
<P>
Exports of agro-industrial products and industrial products
recorded growth in the fourth consecutive month in July, which
rose 11.6 percent and 9.8 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the country's imports also rose 8.5 percent to 27.3
billion dollars in the first seven months of this year.
</P>
<P>
In July, the country imported more vehicles and transport
equipment, up 124.1 percent, followed by raw materials and
semi-finished products.
</P>
<P>
The press release issued after the cabinet meeting Tuesday
attributed the main reason leading to the growth of exports to the
economic recovery in Asia.
</P>
<P>
The efforts made by some joint-venture companies in Thailand,
especially those producing electrical and electronic products, in
seeking new markets with the support of their parent companies
also helped the country's exports to increase as a whole. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
