<HEADLINE> Final Athens Quake Death Toll Reaches 143 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, September 21 (Xinhua) -- A total of 143 people have
been killed in the September 7 earthquake in northwestern Athens,
according to figures released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The final figures were released by the Greek ambulance service,
Attica hospitals and the Athens Mortuary, the semi-official Athens
News Agency (ANA) reported.
</P>
<P>
The earthquake registering 5.9 on the Richter scale occurred at
2:56 p.m. local time, with its epicenter being in the Mount
Parnitha region, some 20 kilometers northwest of Athens.
</P>
<P>
More than 2,000 people were injured and some 60,000 others left
homeless in the earthquake, which is estimated to cost Greece 200
billion drachmas (about 645 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Greece is the sixth most seismically active country in the
world, with earthquakes occurring in the country on an average
rate of once in every five years.
</P>
<P>
The last time Athens was shaken to such an extent was in
February 1981, when an earthquake measuring about 7.1 on the
Richter scale struck the Gulf of Corinth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
