<HEADLINE> UAE Emphasizes Unified Arab Stance Against Disney </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, September 21 (Xinhua) -- The United Arab Emirates
(UAE) Tuesday emphasized the need to take a unified Arab position
against Disney Corp. unless the American entertainment giant bow
to Arabs on a controversial exhibition.
</P>
<P>
Arab countries need to take a unified and decisive position
against Disney if the company does not meet Arab demands on
removing all "displays and other references distorting the
Arab-Islamic identity of Jerusalem" from its exhibition, said UAE
Minister of Information and Culture Sheikh Abdullah Bin Zayed Al
Nahyan in a telephone conversation with his Egyptian counterpart
Safwat Al Sherif.
</P>
<P>
One of Disney's exhibit in the millennium exhibition, due to
open on September 30 at the company's Epcot Center in Orlando,
Florida, depicts Jerusalem as Israel's capital, which has become
the center of a row between Disney and Arab-Islamic countries
recently.
</P>
<P>
Arabs and Muslims accuse Disney of allowing Israel to use its
pavilion to portray Jerusalem as its capital.
</P>
<P>
Israel regards the whole Jerusalem as its "eternal and
indivisible capital" while the Palestinians want Arab East
Jerusalem, captured by Israel since the 1967 Middle East war, to
be capital of the future Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
The UAE and some other countries have threatened to boycott
all Disney products in their markets unless the company convinces
them it will not depict Jerusalem as the Israeli capital.
</P>
<P>
Disney has explained to Arab states that it will go ahead with
the Israeli exhibit, but it will not depict occupied Jerusalem as
Israel's capital.
</P>
<P>
However, the explanations are considered as "not convincing"
and Arab foreign ministers will meet on Friday in New York on the
sidelines of the U.N. General Assembly to further discuss this
issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
