<HEADLINE> Greece's Exports to Yugoslavia Sharply Drops in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Greece's exports to Yugoslavia
dropped by 50 percent in the first half of 1999 following the
overall downward trend due to NATO's bombing of Yugoslavia this
year.
</P>
<P>
Speaking during a meeting with Greek businessmen in the
northern Greek city of Thessaloniki, Yugoslavia's Economic and
Trade Affairs Adviser Christos Farmakis said Tuesday that the
Greek exports to Yugoslavia in the first half of this year reached
76.6 million U.S. dollars while Yugoslavia's exports to Greece
stood at 55 million dollars, the Macedonian Press Agency (MPA)
reported.
</P>
<P>
Greece exported to Yugoslavia mainly petroleum and its
by-products, textile, fruits and vegetables, electricity, tobacco
and tobacco by-products while Yugoslavia's exports to Greece were
mainly made up of metals, rubber products, plastics, leather
products and timber. 
</P>
