<HEADLINE> N.Ireland's Rival Parties Open Talks With Mitchell </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of Northern Ireland's
feuding parties arrived in Belfast for crucial talks with U.S.
mediator Gerorge Mitchell on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Both Ulster Unionist leader David Trimble and Sinn Fein leader
Gerry Adams pledged to be positive in their first talks for two
months. The meeting is one of the most crucial in the Good Friday
agreement review.
</P>
<P>
Adams said it was up to the unionists to prove they were
prepared to implement the troubled peace accord.
</P>
<P>
"There is now a widespread view within nationalism and
republicanism that the political will is absent from the UUP
(Ulster Unionist Party)," Adams told reporters at Castle
Buildings, a government complex in Belfast.
</P>
<P>
Trimble said increased violence, murders and attempted arms
smuggling in recent months put a question mark over republican
commitments to the peace process.
</P>
<P>
He said Sinn Fein had made commitments in the agreement to
peace and democracy, total IRA disarmament and the maintenance of
an unequivocal ceasefire.
</P>
<P>
"They have not yet honored any one of those commitments. It is
time they did," Trimble told reporters.
</P>
<P>
The leaders were arriving for their first round table session
with Mitchell as part of a review, started three weeks ago, of the
problems plaguing the agreement.
</P>
<P>
It was the first top level meeting of delegations between the
parties since abortive talks chaired by British and Irish prime
ministers in July. 
</P>
</TEXT>
