<HEADLINE> Annan Sends Message on Taiwan Quake </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 21 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan Tuesday expressed his sympathy with the people affected
by the massive earthquake in China's Taiwan Province.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by his spokesman reads: "The
Secretary-General learned of the earthquake that struck near
Taipei yesterday with shock and sadness.
</P>
<P>
"He expressed to the people of the Taiwan Province of China his
heartfelt sympathy at this time of trial."
</P>
<P>
A U.N. disaster assessment and coordination team is expected to
arrive in Taipei Wednesday, spokesman Manoel de Almeida e Silva
said.
</P>
<P>
The quake measuring 7.6 on the Richter scale occurred at 1:47
a.m. Beijing time Tuesday with epicenter at southwest Hualien, 90
miles from Taipei. It caused heavy losses.
</P>
<P>
Death toll rose to over 1,600 with thousands more injured or
feared trapped in the rubble.
</P>
<P>
Chinese President Jiang Zemin extended his condolences to the
quake victims, and expressed willingness to offer any possible
assistance to alleviate the losses.
</P>
<P>
The Red Cross Society of China (RCSC) has pledged to provide
emergency assistance, including 100,000 U.S. dollars in relief
funds and 500,000 yuan worth of relief materials to the affected
area. 
</P>
</TEXT>
