<HEADLINE> Singapore Shares Extend Losses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Singapore Shares extended
losses Tuesday amid worries about recovery of the semiconductor
industry after an earthquake shook Taiwan earlier in the day and
disappointing data were released Monday on the country's external
trade in August.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark Straits Times Index (STI) declined 13.89 points
to end at 2,109.4 in fairly quiet trading.
</P>
<P>
Total turnover dropped to 179.55 million units valued at 479.63
million Singapore dollars (282.35 million U.S. dollars). Decliners
outstripped advancers by 255 to 62 with 133 counters unchanged.
</P>
<P>
The larger block was the 12.94 million parcel by Hotung which
was transacted at 0.38 U.S. dollars per share. It was followed by
IPC which registered a volume of 11.34 million units. Gen Int was
the next with 11.26 million shares changing hands.
</P>
<P>
Avimo topped the gainers list, rising 70 cents to finish at
3.00 Singapore dollars. SIA and SIA 200 picked up 40 cents to
close at 18.00 and 17.90 Singapore dollars respectively. SIA
DBScw00 edged up 30 cents to end at 11.60 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, GE Life was the biggest loser of the day
incurring a loss of 100 cents to close at 17.00 Singapore dollars.
Venture sank 70 cents to finish at 14.30 Singapore dollars. Bukit
Sem shed 60 cents to end at 16.00 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said electronics stocks came under selling pressure
partly because of Monday's lower-than-expected growth in the
export of electronic products in August and partly because of
worries about the recovery of the semiconductor industry after an
earthquake struck Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
They also said Avimo's surge-up Tuesday was triggered off by
Monday's announcement by Thomson-CSF of France that it would take
a 24.9 percent stake in the firm. 
