<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa's Inflation Drops in August </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 21 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's inflation
rate dropped by 1.7 percentage points to 3.2 percent in August
compared to 4.9 percent in July, Statistics South Africa announced
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The drop in inflation rate was mainly due to the reduction in
the average interest rates on mortgage bonds from 21.79 percent in
August 1998 to 16.74 percent in August 1999.
</P>
<P>
The annual increase of 3.2 percent in the consumer price index
for metropolitan areas is mainly due to annual increases in the
price indices for transport, food, household operation and medical
care and health expenses.
</P>
<P>
These increases were counteracted by a relatively large annual
decrease in the price index for housing (-1.4 percentage points).
</P>
<P>
The core inflation rate for metropolitan areas was 7.9 percent
in August 1999, representing 0.3 percentage points lower than the
corresponding annual rate of 8.2 percent in July 1999.
</P>
<P>
Core inflation, which excludes mortgages rates, volatile food
item, VAT and assessment rates, is used by the central bank as
basis for its monetary policies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
