<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Decides to Stop Using IMF Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 21 (Xinhua) -- The Thai cabinet Tuesday gave
its approval to the eighth letter of intent to the International
Monetary Fund (IMF), which says that Thailand could exit from the
IMF rescue package worth 17.2 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
According to the letter of intent, Thailand will stop drawing
funds from the IMF rescue package for the time being since several
economic indicators point to a recovering economy.
</P>
<P>
However, the country wants to retain the right to draw funds
from the rest of the package when it feels necessary.
</P>
<P>
So far, Thailand has drawn 13.47 billion dollars from the
bailout package, granted to the country by the IMF in August 1997,
a month after the financial crisis broke out.
</P>
<P>
The letter of intent, the latest review between the government
and the IMF, expects the Thai economy to grow by three to four
percent, compared to the earlier government projection of one
percent.
</P>
<P>
It will be a sharp turnaround from the 10 percent contraction
recorded last year and a fall of 1.8 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Consumer prices have also fallen sharply, with inflation
projected at 0.5 percent for 1999 compared to 8.1 percent in 1998
and 5.6 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The country's foreign reserves, which had depleted to only
about 800 million dollars in August 1997 after a failed baht
defense battle, have been replenished and are expected to rise to
a targeted level of 32 to 34 billion dollars by the end of this
year.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's current account for 1999 is projected at 11.6
billion dollars, or 9.0 percent of the GDP, and overall exports
are expected to reach 55 billion dollars, an increase of four
percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
