<HEADLINE> Italy's GDP Up 0.4 Percent in Second Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Italy's gross domestic product
(GDP) rose 0.4 percent in the second quarter of 1999 over the
first quarter, according to figures released Tuesday by the
Italian statistics bureau Istat.
</P>
<P>
Compared to the second quarter of 1998, GDP growth amounted to
0.8 percent, the same as the first quarter's growth over the same
period last year.
</P>
<P>
Istat said that Italy's GDP figures were "more or less in line"
with other leading industrialized countries, citing France, where
GDP in the second quarter was up 0.6 percent over the first
quarter, and Britain up 0.5 percent, the US up 0.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
"We are not yet witnessing sustained growth but, on the whole,
we can start talking about moderate recovery," the bureau analysts
said.
</P>
<P>
They said that a breakdown of the data for the second quarter
over the first quarter showed that growth was fueled by
consumption, which was up 0.3 percent, while consumption of
investment goods rose 0.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
Imports were up 1.4 percent compared to the first quater, as
were exports, on an annual basis, imports were up a substantial
3.2 percent, while exports were down 2.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
Istat was cautious in its forecasts for the year, limiting
itself to saying that if GDP fails to grow in the third and fourth
quarters, which is unlikely, then growth for the entire year would
come to 0.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
In order to meet its target of GDP growth of 1.2 percent in
1999, Italy will need to post a rise of around 1.6 percent in
annual terms during the second half of the year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
