<HEADLINE> Most Kuwaiti Government Bodies Solve Y2K Problem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, September 21 (Xinhua) -- A Kuwaiti official in
charge of dealing with the Year 2000 (Y2K) computer glitch said on
Tuesday that most of the government bodies in Kuwait have overcome
the millennium problem.
</P>
<P>
Faisal Al-Shaygi, deputy chairman of the Central Work Team
assigned to follow up the Y2K bug, told a news conference here
that the conclusion was reached after the team had analyzed the
situation of 33 government departments.
</P>
<P>
The bug dates back to the early days of computer programming
when only the last two numbers of the year were used in most
software. If the problem is not solved, some computers will read
2000 as 1900 and shut off or give wrong answers when the new
century starts.
</P>
<P>
The work team, which was formed in August by the Planning
Ministry, was responsible for examining the systems of the
computers used by government bodies and mapping out an emergency
strategy to cope with the problem.
</P>
<P>
Shaygi said government departments were divided into two
categories. The first category comprises 18, of which some have
connection with security and vital economic services and need to
be completely ready for the Y2K problem.
</P>
<P>
The second batch includes 34 bodies which are less risky and
have alternatives in case of emergency, he said.
</P>
<P>
But the official said that a small number of institutions are
still in need for some equipment to prepare for the global
problem.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990922.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Foreign Minister Voices Firm Opposition to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Russian Foreign
Minister Igor Ivaonov Tuesday listed separatism as one of the main
threats and challenges facing the world today, calling upon the
United Nations to take decisive steps to crack down separatist
moves in defense of the principles of sovereignty and territorial
integrity.
</P>
<P>
"Aggressive separatism, which became a fertile soil for various
extremist forces, has turned into one of the main sources of
domestic conflicts and regional unsuitability," he said. "Nobody
is safeguarded against it."
</P>
<P>
"International community and, first of all, the United Nations
should decisively clamp down on any manifestations of separatism
and strictly and consistently defend the principles of
sovereignty, territorial integrity and inviolability of the
national borders," he said.
</P>
<P>
The statement came as the Russian foreign minister was
delivering his speech at the general debate of the 53rd General
Assembly session, which, beginning Monday, is scheduled to last
two weeks.
</P>
<P>
"It is necessary to completely eradicate instances of
encouragement and support for separatist forces from without," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"We are fully aware of the danger posed by threats and
challenges, that our world faces today, e.g. military nationalism,
separatism, terrorism and extremism regardless of their forms have
no borders," he said. "It is a common challenge claiming countless
victims and bringing destruction to various places on our planet."
</P>
<P>
"Recently separatism has been increasingly merging with the
monster of terrorism," he said. "Even during this session we could
undertake several concrete steps aimed at a move active practical
international cooperation in combating terrorism."
</P>
<P>
"It is necessary to finalize the draft Convention on Fighting
Acts of Nuclear Terrorism," he said. "We also propose to develop
and adopt a declaration of principles of interaction between states
with the view to stepping up the fight against terrorism."
</P>
<P>
"It is a bounded duty of states to protect their citizens
against terrorist encroachment and to prevent on their territories
activities aimed at organizing such acts against citizens of other
countries," said the foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
Russia also supports the initiative of holding an
anti-terrorist conference under the auspices of the United Nations
or a special session of the U.N. General Assembly in 2000.
</P>
<P>
"This event would give a powerful political impetus to the
struggle against terrorism at a global level," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
