<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambique to Launch Strategic Plan Against AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Mozambique will launch a
National Strategic Plan to fight against the wide-spreading of
AIDS in the southern African country.
</P>
<P>
The government started a conference Tuesday to discuss the
draft National Strategic Plan for the fight against Sexually
Transmitted Diseases (STD) and HIV/AIDS.
</P>
<P>
According to the plan, the government will allocate some 40
million U.S. dollars in the next three years to control this
deadly disease in the poverty-stricken country.
</P>
<P>
Health authorities estimate that about 700 people in the
country are getting infected with HIV every day.
</P>
<P>
Figures from the Health Ministry show that there are 11,300
people have died of AIDS since 1986, when the first case was
diagnosed in Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
However, the director of the Epidemic Department in the
Ministry, Avertino Barreto, says that this figure is
underestimated.
</P>
<P>
Most AIDS deaths are not included in this figure simply
because they did not take place in any health unit. It is also
certain that many cases have gone undiagnosed.
</P>
<P>
Barreto said the current estimation of 900,000 people
suffering from AIDS in the country is believed to be lower than
the real figure.
</P>
<P>
Governor of the central province of Manica, Felicio Zacarias,
said that his province is one of the most affected by AIDS because
of poverty, associated with illiteracy and poor access to health
care.
</P>
<P>
"Because of all this we find ourselves in a situation, where
AIDS has started affecting the development of our provinces,
creating instability in work places, and destroying the social
family fabric. All in all, it tends to throw us into even greater
poverty," said Zacarias.

NNNN
03:57 03:58 g # PAB
</P>
