<HEADLINE> SADC Central Banks Prepare for Regional </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Central banks of the
Southern African Development Community (SADC) are developing the
financial architecture which could form the basis of closer
regional economic integration, South African Reserve Bank Governor
Tito Mboweni said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Mboweni, who is also the chairperson of the SADC committee of
central bank governors, said the committee was slowly but surely
laying the foundation for a robust regional economic bloc.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the University of Pretoria, Mboweni said the SADC
finance and investment sector was convinced that it had already
laid the foundation for macroeconomic convergence and integration.
</P>
<P>
Mboweni would make every effort to ensure "that we continue
with the construction of a strong financial infrastructure for the
region, so that globalization can work to the advantage of the
Southern African region."
</P>
<P>
A target implementation date had been set for January next year
to begin the process of lowering trade barriers, streamlining
customs and border procedures, and harmonizing external tariffs,
he said.
</P>
<P>
"We understand that South Africa plans to eliminate most duties
on imported goods from other SADC countries by 2004, and the
region could ultimately develop into a free trade zone."
</P>
<P>
The work being done by the committee of central bank governors
constituted an important building block toward the creation of a
free trade zone.
</P>
<P>
"One cannot implement free trade in goods and services without
having the proper financial systems in place. The work of the
Committee of Central Bank Governors can be seen as providing the
oil that makes the wheels of commerce turn faster in the region."
</P>
<P>
Before full economic integration could be attained, the region
needed sound financial systems that could withstand sudden
international shocks and which could accommodate increased
economic activity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
