<HEADLINE> Ghana Voices Confidence in United Nations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Ghana Tuesday voiced
its confidence in the ability of the United Nations to achieve
sustainable socio-economic development, and called for a reform
for the world body in order to enable it to be more effective to
act under the U.N. Charter.
</P>
<P>
The statement came as Jerry Rawlings, president of Ghana, took
the floor at the general debate of the 54th General Assembly
session, which began Monday.
</P>
<P>
"The situation is aggravated by the multiplicity of conflicts
that pervades the world, especially in Africa," he said.
"Intra-state conflicts, rooted in ethnic, racial and religious
intolerance pose a threat to the security and stability of many
states and regions."
</P>
<P>
"In spite of such setbacks and disappointments, we must
continue to maintain trust and confidence in the U.N.'s ability
to achieve sustainable socio-economic development for member
states," he said.
</P>
<P>
"But that confidence will be sustained only when the
Organization is seen to be truly seeking the interest of all
member states, without exception," he said.
</P>
<P>
"In that regard, member states must give impetus to the reform
process that we initiated a decade ago and maintain its dynamism,"
he said. "We also must accept that the core of the reform touches
on the Security Council whose decisions bind all members of the
Organization."
</P>
<P>
"The Security Council must therefore not be allowed to become
irrelevant," he said. "It should be reformed to ensure that it can
undertake its responsibility more effectively under the Charter."
</P>
<P>
"This reform must be guided by the principles of democracy,
sovereign equality of states and equitable geographical
representation," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
