<HEADLINE> SADC Defense Chiefs to Meet in Swaziland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Defense chiefs from
Southern African Development Community (SADC) countries will meet
in Swaziland Wednesday to discuss conflicts in the region, a Swazi
army spokesman said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Reports reaching here quoted the spokesman, Sotja Dlamini, as
saying that the defense chiefs would hold two days of talks in the
convention center in the Swaziland capital, Mbabane.
</P>
<P>
Dlamini later told reporters that the meeting would discuss the
ongoing conflicts in the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC)
and in Angola.
</P>
<P>
"The defense chiefs will also discuss other matters pertaining
to security in the region," he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that all 14 members of SADC would be represented at
the conference.
</P>
<P>
The meeting in the Swazi kingdom follows talks in Pretoria on
Monday between the defense ministers of South Africa and Zimbabwe,
and Swaziland Foreign Minister Albert Shabangu, over a southern
African policy for dealing with regional wars.
</P>
<P>
The goal of the meetings, Shabangu told reporters afterwards,
is the development of a protocol governing SADC's reaction to
"situations that require intervention, peacekeeping or peace
enforcement."
</P>
<P>
The protocol is expected to be endorsed by all 14 SADC members,
said Shabangu, who heads the SADC inter-state defense and security
committee.
</P>
<P>
But he added that it was too early to say when the protocol
would be ready.
</P>
<P>
SADC's defense policy came under scrutiny last year when South
Africa and Botswana launched a joint military intervention mission
in the troubled kingdom of Lesotho to stave off a coup. 
</P>
</TEXT>
