<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Summers Says U.S. Continues to Help Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 21 (Xinhua) -- The United States said
Tuesday it would continue to support Russia or risk being branded
as "scapegoats" for Russia's failure but should not back any new
multinational loans until adequate safeguards were ensured.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the hearing of the Banking Committee of the House,
Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers said the administration will
support Russia in economic development in spite of allegations
that aid to Russia has been illegally diverted.
</P>
<P>
"The American people have an enormous national security,
economic, and law enforcement stake in a peaceful and successful
transition to a law-based, democratic market economy in Russia,"
Summers told the congressmen.
</P>
<P>
The panel planned a series of hearings into the allegations
that up to 10 billion U.S. dollars including aid from the
international institutions have been channeled illegally to the
Bank of New York in the past year.
</P>
<P>
Citing the nuclear arsenal Russia still has and the importance
of a strong and stable global economy, Summer stressed that the
United States has crucial interests in supporting Russia's
economic and political reform.
</P>
<P>
"Acting on that view would limit our ability to support Russian
economic and financial stability... it would raise the risk that
the United States and the West would be labeled as scapegoats for
Russia's failure to address its problems," Summers said.
</P>
<P>
"To quarantine, contain or write off Russia as too corrupt
would ill serve our national interest," Summers told the
committee.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the "crucial multilateral tool to support
economic reform in Russia has been conditional finance from the
international financial institutions."
</P>
<P>
"Given the pervasive problems in the rule of law in Russia,
we do not believe at this point that the provision of new funds
would be constructive," Summers said.
</P>
<P>
The current allegations involving money laundering through
major American banks "only reinforce our recognition that
widespread corruption in Russia can pose a significant danger to
our interests," he added.
</P>
<P>
Safeguarding the integrity of the U.S. financial system was a
key priority, said Summers. "We are committed to the full
investigation of these allegations."
</P>
<P>
The Clinton administration plans to unveil Thursday a new
strategy on fighting money-laundering.
</P>
<P>
Also on Tuesday, Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov said
Russia also wants to have a full investigation of the allegations
because people of Russia are the victims if the allegations were
proved to be true.
</P>
<P>
Ivanov made the remarks when meeting U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright in New York while they attended the U.N.
Assembly meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
