<HEADLINE> Mexico, EU to Start New Round of Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, September 21 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU)
and Mexico will begin their eighth round of trade talks on October
7, said a spokesman from the EU Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
According to reports reaching here from Brussels, the meeting
was scheduled to be held in Mexico on September 27, but was
postponed because the EU are still analyzing their proposal.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman from the European Commission said that the
Europeans want the next meeting to be "substantial" now that they
have planned to make a definitive agreement in their negotiations
with Mexico before the end of 1999.
</P>
<P>
He added that the rules of origin are a very delicate theme
because the EU has certain ruling norms, and making a change with
Mexico signifies changes within the EU also.
</P>
<P>
The rules of origin are a very sensitive theme in the
negotiations it has with Mexico, as they determine the conditions
which a product must adhere, with respect to Value Added Tax
(VAT).
</P>
<P>
Another of the delicate themes which are included in the next
negotiations is the lowering of duties of tariffs.
</P>
<P>
The EU are offering Mexico 82 percent of industrial products
free of tariffs, once the agreement is begun; the other 18 percent
to be applied in the year 2003.
</P>
<P>
For their part, the Mexican authorities proposed a lowering of
duties for periods which would begin with 48 percent at the
beginning of the agreement, a further 4 percent in 2003, another 6
percent in the year 2005, and the remaining 42 percent in the year
2007. 
</P>
</TEXT>
