<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wolfensohn Calls For Intensifying Fight Against Poverty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 21 (Xinhua) -- World Bank President Jim
Wolfensohn called here Tuesday for intensifying the fight against
poverty as the world is entering into a new millennium.
</P>
<P>
As the economic statistics are a lot better in East Asia this
year, "the thing that is of still deepest concern to us is that
the poverty levels are so high," Wolfensohn said at a press
conference before the start of the annual meetings of the World
Bank and the International Monetary Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
He said that in a number of days there will be 6 billion people
on the planet, and of them, 3 billion will live under two dollars
a day, and 1.3 billion under one dollar a day.
</P>
<P>
In the next 25 years there will be 8 billion people on the
planet, and if nothing is done, 4 billion will live under two
dollars a day and up to 2 billion in extreme poverty, he added.
</P>
<P>
Forgiving debt is a very important precondition to dealing with
poverty, but forgiving debt itself doesn't generate money and it
doesn't generate a flow of resources, Wolfensohn said.
</P>
<P>
"Unless we've had development assistance as well and unless we
have an additional commitment from countries around the world who
are concerned with this issue, we achieve something with debt
forgiveness," he said.
</P>
<P>
Wolfensohn said it is important for people in developed and
developing countries to recognize that poverty is everybody's
issue.
</P>
<P>
"As we move into the next millennium, we've got to think of
ourselves not just as residents of our own country but residents
of the planet," he said.
</P>
<P>
"If you ask me what needs to be done, first is raising the
awareness," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
