<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Official Calls for Reform of  African Local </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 21 (Xinhua) -- African countries cannot
reverse the negative trends of poverty and diseases unless a
common vision for local government is developed in the next
millennium, an official said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
President of the African Union of Local Authorities (AULA)
Patrick Wanyeraw was speaking at the start of a three-day
ministers conference on " challenges facing local government in
Africa in the 21st century" in Victoria Falls town, Zimbabwe News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
He said the common vision should resolve issues such as making
local government more democratic, transparent and accountable to
citizens.
</P>
<P>
"AULA notes with a degree of satisfaction that central
government ministers responsible for local government in Africa
have begun to take an unavoidable active part in seriously
reviewing the manner in which local government has been
functioning," he said.
</P>
<P>
!0They are trying to come up with a common position regarding
local development and setting up a sustainable local government
institutions," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said AULA was developing a worldwide charter of local
governance which would be presented to the United Nations General
Assembly in the next few years.
</P>
<P>
He said the idea of the charter was to agree on a general local
 government framework and principles within which nations could
design their systems of governance at local level.
</P>
<P>
"It should also be appreciated that local government is not
sitting idle in view of the important lobbying central governments
are doing in respect of debt burdens that are causing havoc among
our people," he said.
</P>
<P>
Local governments were also putting pressure to encourage rich
nations to review the terms of debts owed by poor African nations,
he said.
</P>
<P>
The broad objective of the conference which opened on Tuesday
is to provide an opportunity for ministers together with town
clerks and mayors to share experience and lessons emanating from
ongoing process of decentralization and related reforms.
</P>
<P>
Over 100 participants from 14 countries are attending the
conference.  
</P>
</TEXT>
