<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli PM Says Israel Will Not Pay Any Price for Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak said in an interview with French daily Le Monde published on
Tuesday that Israel will not pay any price for making peace with
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
He said that Israel will not make any compromise about the
status of Jerusalem, claimed as the capital city by both Israelis
and Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
"Listen, our position is clear: a Jerusalem united, eternal
capital of Israel, one point, that's all," he said.
</P>
<P>
Israel captured the eastern part of Jerusalem from Jordan in
the 1967 Middle East War.
</P>
<P>
He also said although talks will be tough, peace process is the
only way for both Israel and its Arab neighbors to go out of the
present impasse.
</P>
<P>
"If we make them (Palestinians) understand that we will not
compromise on our vital interests in security matters but at the
same we want peace and are ready to listen to their needs and
their interests, I think we will get a deal," he said.
</P>
<P>
But he said that Israel will not make peace at any price or
under any condition.
</P>
<P>
Barak gave the interview in the Israeli Defense Ministry, where
he still holds the minister's portfolio, before starting his visit
to Europe on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Israel and Palestinians signed a new agreement this month on a
partial withdrawal of Israeli troops from the West Bank in
exchange for peace with Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Barak said that no one should expect him to dismantle or
downsize the defense capacities of Israel, because "our strength
will remain the only guarantee of our survival for years, even
generations."
</P>
<P>
"But instead of continuing to invest such resources to face off
a perpetual animosity, why not try seriously to solve in depth the
questions which cause such animosity?" he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
