<HEADLINE> African Ministers Call on Decentralization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 21 (Xinhua) (C African ministers attending a
local government conference in Zimbabwe's Victoria Falls Tuesday
resolved to lobby their respective countries to implement the
policy of decentralization as a way of promoting development,
accountability and transparency.
</P>
<P>
Gambia's Secretary of State for Local Government, Lands and
Religious Affairs Lamin Kaba Bajo said there was need to muster
more political and administrative support for decentralization.
</P>
<P>
He said this was because there were many cases of central
government reluctance to devolve authority and create enabling
environments for decentralization and local empowerment.
</P>
<P>
Uganda's minister of local government Jaberi Bindandi-Sali said
raising civic competence, improving service delivery,
democratizing society and mounting an effective attack against
poverty presupposes the establishment of a transparent,
representative local government system.
</P>
<P>
He said such a system required several pre-conditions in order
to take root and flourish, such as the devolution of power to
local governments and enacting legislation to clearly articulate
the respective roles of central and local governments.
</P>
<P>
Sali said local government councilors and civil servants should
also have a clear understanding of their respective roles and
responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
"Effective revenue mobilization, both internal and external,
must be undertaken and the system must enjoy total conviction and
commitment at the highest political levels," he said.
</P>
<P>
Other ministers said the policy of decentralization should be
enshrined in constitutions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
