<HEADLINE> U.S. Force Stands by in Darwin for East Timor Operation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 21 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. troops to be
involved in a multinational force in East Timor are now standing
by in Australia and will be near its full strength of 200 by
Wednesday, the Pentagon said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
They would remain in Darwin, Australia, until the Australian
commander of the multinational force, Maj. Gen. Peter Gosgrove,
decides they are needed in East Timor, said P.J. Crowley, deputy
assistant secretary of defense for public affairs.
</P>
<P>
"We are set to go whenever the commander feels those
capabilities are needed," Crowley told a Pentagon briefing.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. troops include mostly specialists in communications,
supply and intelligence with no combat troops.
</P>
<P>
There are only two U.S. soldiers -- a Marine liaison officer
and a public affairs officer -- in East Timor Tuesday after Marine
Brig. Gen. John Castellaw and four other marines returned to
Darwin where the U.S. force have reached 140. Another 50 soldiers
from around the Pacific were expected by Wednesday. And 14 civil
affairs personnel left Fort Bragg, N.C., for Darwin Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the ground force, 527 U.S. personnel were
aboard two U.S. Navy ships in the area -- the guided missile
cruiser USS Mobile Bay and the ammunition ship USNS Kilavea,
Crowley said.
</P>
<P>
Three U.S. helicopters were available on the ships for
possible use in East Timor and a Marine KC 130 cargo plane had
made at least one flight carrying Australians into the region,
Crowley added. Three other U.S. transport planes also were in
Darwin for the operation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
