<HEADLINE> Chiluba Urges Security Council to Promote Peace in Congo (K) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Zambian President
Frederick Chiluba Tuesday called on the U.N. Security Council to
authorize and support the deployment of a peacekeeping force in
the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC), and assist with resources
for the economic reconstruction and development in the African
country.
</P>
<P>
The president, who mediated a ceasefire among warring parties
in Congo (K), made the appeal at an open meeting of the 15-nation
Security Council, held at the request of Gabon.
</P>
<P>
"I wish to request the Security Council to, among other things,
authorize and support the deployment of a peacekeeping force in
the DRC with an appropriate mandate and size, based on the
assessed needs on the ground," said the president.
</P>
<P>
He also called upon the Security Council to "quickly dispatch
the Technical Survey team to the DRC, in addition to the team of
Military Liaison personnel which has already been sent to the DRC
and some neighboring countries."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he said that the Security Council should "make
available adequate resources for the DRC peacekeeping mission,"
and "extend necessary and adequate support to facilitate the
process of internal Congolese dialogue."
</P>
<P>
He also asked the Security Council "to help in the mobilization
of humanitarian assistance to Congolese refugees and internally
displaced persons, and facilitate their return and resettlement,"
and "assist with resources for the economic reconstruction and
development of the DRC."
</P>
<P>
The president reminded the Security Council "that there is a
perception that the U.N., and in particular the Security Council,
is usually slow and reluctant to support peace efforts in Africa."
</P>
<P>
"The body is seen to be more forth-coming when dealing with
peace efforts in other regions, even though Africa forms the
largest component of the membership of the U.N.," he said. "I,
therefore, hope that the Security Council will act with due
proportion and understanding in dealing with the situation in the
DRC."
</P>
<P>
The open meeting came one day before defense ministers from the
14-nation Southern African Development Community is scheduled to
hold a meeting in Swaziland to discuss wars in the DRC and Angola
that threaten the stability in Africa.
</P>
<P>
In the wake of a year-long mediation by African countries, a
ceasefire to end the Congo (K) conflict was first signed by Congo
(K) and its allies, Angola, Namibia and Zimbabwe, and rebel
backers Rwanda and Uganda. The peace accord was later endorsed
by a rebel group on August 31.
</P>
<P>
The brutal 13-month war has displaced hundreds of thousands of
people and is seen as a major threat to stability and development
in Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
