<HEADLINE> European Stock Markets Go Into A Slide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 21 (Xinhua) -- European markets closed firmly
in the red Tuesday after a larger-than-expected U.S. trade deficit
further deepened the gloom caused by fears of higher interest
rates.
</P>
<P>
London posted the biggest losses, with the FTSE 100 touching a
seven-month low. The blue-chip index fell 99 points, or 1.6
percent, to 5,957.3, breaking the psychological 6,000 barrier for
the first time in five weeks.
</P>
<P>
The fall began early on as heavyweight oil companies slid ahead
of this week's meeting of oil producing countries to discuss
production limits.
</P>
<P>
BP Amoco, which closed down 1.7 percent, and Shell down 3.6
percent dominated the Footsie and their falls dragged the whole
index downwards.
</P>
<P>
Rate-sensitive financial stocks were the biggest losers on the
session, wiping some 20 points off the index. Insurer Sun Life &AMP;
Provincial was the biggest decliner on the FTSE as it tumbled 7.7
percent, while Prudential shed 4.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
Banking leader Lloyds TSB fell 3.1 percent, while one of its
counterparts in the telecom sector, British Telecommunications,
fell 4.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
German shares closed lower as the market reacted to the early
sharp fall on Wall Street. The benchmark Dax index closed at
5,282.76, down 66.12.
</P>
<P>
In Paris shares closed lower across the board after Wall
Street's early drop hit late trading in France. The CAC-40 index
was 67.56 points lower at 4,612.93. 
</P>
</TEXT>
