<HEADLINE> Israel Angry About Mandate of Newly-Named UN Mideast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Israel on Tuesday
protested that the newly appointed U.N. coordinator for the
Mideast peace process has broader mandate than his predecessor.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan on Tuesday named Terje
Roed-Larsen of Norway as U.N. special coordinator for the Middle
East peace process and his Personal Representative to the
Palestine Liberation Organization and the Palestinian Authority.
</P>
<P>
Roed-Larsen will succeed Indian diplomat Chinmaya Gharekhan who
would leave his post on September 30 as U.N. special
representative to multilateral talks on Middle East peace process
and as U.N. special coordinator in the occupied territories.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by Israel's U.N. mission said Israel had
"repeatedly clarified to the U.N. and its representative that it
cannot accept an expansion of the title, mandate and powers of
the outgoing U.N. special coordinator ...beyond the economic
functional area to which he was charged."
</P>
<P>
"Any attempt to alter these terms of reference, including
the involvement of the United Nations in the negotiating
process, are unacceptable to the government of Israel," the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
The statement said the basis of the Arab-Israeli peace process
since the 1991 Madrid Peace Conference had been "direct,
face-to-face negotiations between the parties."
</P>
<P>
In a letter to the United Nations Security Council, Annan said
Roed-Larsen's duties as the new U.N. special coordinator "take
into account recent encouraging developments in the Middle East
peace process," particularly the resumption of Israeli-Palestinian
negotiations and the prospects for renewed talks in other
bilateral tracks.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Chief said Roed-Larsen would have the task of making
"appropriate preparations within the United Nations for enhancing
U.N. development assistance in support of the peace process."
</P>
<P>
The new special coordinator will also represent the
Secretary-General in discussions with the parties and the
international community "in all matters related to continuing
United Nations support to the peace process," said Annan.
</P>
<P>
Roed-Larsen would take up his new post on October 1, 1999,
Annan said.
</P>
<P>
Roed-Larsen served as the first U.N. special coordinator in
the occupied territories from June 1994 to October 1996.  
</P>
</TEXT>
