<HEADLINE> Saudis to Back Possible Arab Boycott of Disney </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Saudi Arabia said on
Wednesday it will support any possible Arab League boycott of the
U.S. entertainment giant Walt Disney Corporation over an
exhibition dispute.
</P>
<P>
"Saudi Arabia is committed to back moves by the Arab League," a
Saudi spokesman told the official Saudi Press Agency.
</P>
<P>
He said the Gulf kingdom would stand behind any move to be
adopted by the Arab foreign ministers during their consultative
meeting due in New York on Friday on the sidelines of the annual
United Nations General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
One of Disney's exhibit in the millennium exhibition, due to
open on September 30 at the company's Epcot Center in Orlando,
Florida, depicts Jerusalem as Israel's capital, which has become
the center of a row between Disney and Arab-Islamic countries
recently.
</P>
<P>
Israel regards the whole Jerusalem as its "eternal and
indivisible capital" while the Palestinians want Arab East
Jerusalem, captured by Israel in the 1967 Middle East war, to be
capital of the future Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
The Saudi spokesman said the Cairo-based Arab League previously
decided to contact Disney over the issue.
</P>
<P>
Disney has explained to Arab states that it will go ahead with
the Israeli exhibit, but it will not depict occupied Jerusalem as
Israel's capital.
</P>
<P>
However, the explanations are considered as "not convincing"
and several Arab states have threatened to boycott Disney's
products and service unless the company met the demands of Arab
states.
</P>
<P>
Jerusalem has always been one of the most sensitive issues
between the Palestinians and the Israelis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
