<HEADLINE> China Beat South Korea at Asian Women's Volleyball </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese women spikers
Wednesday vanquished their arch-rivals South Korea in full sets,
booking their berth in the four-team finals with a clean slate at
the Asian Women's Volleyball Championship here.
</P>
<P>
"Our team are young, they are a little bit nervous in the court,
" said Chinese coach Hu Jin who took charge of the national team
again in March.
</P>
<P>
He added that he was "very satisfied" with his team and
believed that they could perform better if they took the advantage
at the net.
</P>
<P>
The win put world and Olympic runners-up China not only into
the round-robin finals, but also into an advantage to defend the
title seven times in a row because the Chinese win over South
Korea will be carried into the finals.
</P>
<P>
The finals will pick up top two finishers of the two groups.
South Korea secured the finals berth on Tuesday with three wins
and one loss in Group B while Japan and Thailand ranked top two in
Group A.
</P>
<P>
In Wednesday's other matches, Japan defeated Chinese Taipei 3-0
and remained undefeated in three matches of Group A and Thailand
outclassed lowly-rated hosts Hong Kong, China 3-0 to finish second
in the group with two wins and one loss.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the match against South Korea, Hu Jin said: "I'm
quite happy with my team's performance today."
</P>
<P>
South Korean coach Kim Cheol Yong said he would not wait long
before taking a revenge.
</P>
<P>
"But I am still confident that my team will beat China sooner
or later," said Kim Cheol Yong, who re-coached South Korea's
national team early this year after South Korea suffered a loss to
China in the finals at the Asian Games last year.
</P>
<P>
Kim led South Korea's surprise victory over China, taking the
gold in Hiroshima Asian Games in 1994.
</P>
<P>
The clash between China and South Korea was regarded as the
title's fight in advance.
</P>
<P>
Local crowd favorites China got a slow start when they left
behind 0-4. But they soon controlled the game and led the score
all the way up to 24-20 with powerful serving and tight blocking.
</P>
<P>
But the fighting Koreans came from behind to level the score at
24-all by saving four set points. Then the game was tied 5 times
before China sealed the tough set due to their opponents' erratic
smashes.
</P>
<P>
The second and third sets saw the Koreans dominating the net
and displaying solid defense, winning the two sets 25-19, 25-21.
</P>
<P>
The fourth set was a see-saw affair and the scores were leveled
12 times before China took the set at 25-23.
</P>
<P>
Koreans raced to a lead at 12-9 in the decider. Then China
fought back to tie at 12-all. And the game was the repeat of the
first set, leveling eight times in a row before China finished the
125-minute tussle with a score of 22-20. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
