<HEADLINE> Measures Announced to Boost Competitiveness of HK Airport </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The landing and parking
charges for all aircraft at the Hong Kong International Airport
are proposed to be reduced by 15 percent with effect from January
1, 2000, Victor Fung, chairman of the Hong Kong Airport Authority,
announced here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
This is one of the measures announced by Fung for increasing
the competitive edge of the Hong Kong International Airport.
</P>
<P>
Other measures include invitation for expressions of interest
for the construction of logistics centers at the airport and
invitation for expressions of interest for the construction of a
marine cargo terminal at the airport.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that the reduction in charges will provide a timely
incentive to the development of aviation into Hong Kong and to the
highly competitive and price-sensitive air freight market in
particular," Fung said.
</P>
<P>
"Taken as a whole, the three measures will allow Hong Kong to
further strengthen its position as the airfreight hub of Asia," he
added. The Hong Kong International Airport is number one in the
world in international air cargo and number five in international
passengers.
</P>
<P>
Fung added that the reduction in charges would also enable the
airlines to offer more competitive, value-added services, and in
particular that they would bring in additional passenger traffic
and to develop new routes into Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
It was expected that the airlines would pass on a substantial
portion of these reductions to benefit local residents and
visitors alike, and should provide a welcome boost to the tourist
industry.
</P>
<P>
The logistics center will provide state-of-the-art facilities
for automated storage, customizing and retrieval systems. The
marine cargo terminal will handle air cargo arriving by sea from
the Pearl River Delta in southern China.
</P>
<P>
Fung said that the reduction in charges would be subject to
approval by the Chief Executive in Council, and will be reviewed
annually.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong government expressed its welcome to the measures
on Wednesday, saying that these measures will help enhance Hong
Kong's position as a major air cargo hub and will also benefit
Hong Kong's traders, transport operators and the air cargo
industry.
</P>
<P>
The Board of Airlines Representatives, which represents all
airlines operating at Hong Kong International Airport, and the
Hong Kong Tourist Association have also expressed their welcome to
the measures. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
