<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Hopes Cyprus Peace Talks to Start Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The United States is hopeful
that talks over the Cyprus issue will take place in the near
future, the U.S. ambassador in Nicosia Donald Bandler said here
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after meeting with Cyprus' Socialist Edek Party
leader Vassos Lyssarides, Bandler said what is important is "to
begin the comprehensive talks" and that it doesn't matter whether
the talks begin "indirectly, directly or some other combination."
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Turkish Cypriots-controlled
north and the Greek Cypriots-dominated south since 1974 when
Turkish troops invaded and occupied the northern third of the
island in the wake of a failed coup seeking union with Athens.
</P>
<P>
Since then, the international community has been trying to
bring the two sides to negotiate for reunification through a
bicommunal settlement. But no tangible progress has been achieved.
</P>
<P>
The seven most industrialized nations plus Russia (G-8), in
their June summit in Cologne, Germany, asked the United Nations
Secretary General Kofi Annan to invite leaders of the two
communities to unconditional negotiations in the fall of 1999.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus President Glafcos Clerides has said he expects to be
invited to talks in the second half of October.
</P>
<P>
However, the prospect of holding such meetings remains gloomy
as Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash insists that he would not
enter into negotiations unless his breakaway state in northern
Cyprus, backed by Turkey, be internationally recognized and talk
with Nicosia on equal basis.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the current situation, Lyssarides said he did not
believe peace talks, even if possible now, would yield any better
results than previous attempts.
</P>
<P>
"I do not see any change in Turkey's positions and therefore I
do not expect that it is possible to get better results from this
round of negotiations," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
