<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO to Reduce Military Force in Balkans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 22 (Xinhua) -- NATO defense ministers agreed
to streamline their military operations in the Balkans by cutting
the number of troops in Bosnia by one-third and reorganizing those
remaining into a more cost-effective force.
</P>
<P>
At a two-day informal meeting of defense ministers and generals
from the 19 NATO nations, Javier Solana, NATO's secretary-general,
said on Tuesday that a cut in peacekeeping forces in the Balkans
is possible due to the improved security situation in Bosnia and
the demilitarization of the Kosovo Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
"We have analyzed the situation in Bosnia and it is true that
the situation today permits a rationalization of the deployment of
the force which is on the ground," Solana said.
</P>
<P>
Formal approval of the plan is expected later this fall.
</P>
<P>
Solana said this might mean combining NATO forces in the region
into a single Balkans command, although merging the forces
completely would not be possible because the two conflicts are
quite different, with a peace agreement in Bosnia but no such deal
in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
NATO countries now have 80,000 peacekeeping troops deployed in
five Balkan states including Bosnia, Croatia, Macedonia, Albania
and the Yugoslav province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Under the plan tentatively agreed to by the allies, a strong
presence would remain in Kosovo to guard the fragile peace, but
the number of troops in Bosnia would be reduced to 21,000, from
the current 30,000, over the winter and the forces would be
reorganized to cut costs.
</P>
<P>
The discussions on Tuesday in Toronto were the first since the
war with Yugoslavia and were understandably focused on the Balkans.
A post-mortem of the NATO intervention in Kosovo was a key item on
the agenda. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
