<HEADLINE> Major News Items in U.S. Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The following are major
news items in leading U.S. newspapers Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post:
</P>
<P>
-- The FDA approved an antibiotic to treat hospital patients
infected with bacteria that are resistant to all other drugs.
</P>
<P>
-- The Justice Department plans to against the major tobacco
companies as early as Wednesday, alleging that cigarette smoking
costs the federal government billions of dollars annually in
health-related expenses.
</P>
<P>
The New York Times:
</P>
<P>
-- Closing statements were delivered in the year-old Microsoft
antitrust trial. The Judge's ruling is expected around the end of
the year.
</P>
<P>
-- Bell Atlantic and Britain's Vodafone Airtouch will combine
their United States wireless operations.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal:
</P>
<P>
-- DaimlerChrysler could announce as early as Friday a
restructuring of top management that is expected to enhance the
authority of Chairman Juergen Schrempp and his allies.
</P>
<P>
-- OPEC energy ministers headed into their formal meeting with
unusual resolve to keep production cutbacks in place, a move
expected to keep oil prices at more than 20 U.S. Dollars a barrel.
</P>
