<HEADLINE> Greece Denies Reports to Better Ties With Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Greece denied Wednesday that
Foreign Minister George Papandreou had ever raised an issue of
improving relations with Turkey without preconditions.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press briefing, Greek government spokesman
Dimitris Reppas said that there was a climate of non-tension,
referring to the present state of Greek-Turkish relations.
</P>
<P>
He said that a second round of talks between senior
Greek-Turkish Foreign Ministry officials on finding common ground
for rapprochement had ended and that a third round of such talks
would begin at the end of October.
</P>
<P>
As for Turkey's accession to the European Union (EU), the
spokesman stressed that the neighboring country must show such
behavior which would illustrate that it was coming into line with
European interests.
</P>
<P>
Greece has insisted that Turkey can not join the EU unless
Ankara improves its human rights record and its relations with
Athens.
</P>
<P>
Greece and Turkey, both NATO members, have been at odds for
decades over their disputes in the territorial waters, air space
limits, the delimitation of the continental shelf in the Aegean
Sea and the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
The two countries have since this year began to hold talks with
the aim of creating a favorable climate for the improvement of
their strained relations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
