<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "Principle of Sovereignty Must be Upheld," Italy Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Italian Foreign
Minister Lamberto Dini said here Wednesday that "the principle of
sovereignty must be upheld," and the case of Kosovo can not be
repeated in the future.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister told a press conference that "the
intervention in Kosovo took place without the mandate by the
United Nations," thus raising an issue of legitimacy in
humanitarian interventions.
</P>
<P>
On the case of Kosovo, a Yugoslav province, he said that the
international community can not take the law into its hand by
waging intervention in a sovereign country under the pretext of
the urgency of the situation in the target country.
</P>
<P>
"This one can not be repeated," he said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S.-led NATO, without the authorisation of the Security
Council, launched a unilateral military action against Yugoslavia,
a sovereign and independent member of the U.N. family. Under the
U.N. Charter, the Security Council has the primary responsibility
for the maintenance of the world peace and security.
</P>
<P>
In the future, "we should enhance crisis prevention rather than
conflict suppression," and "we should only use force as a last
resort."
</P>
<P>
On the reform of the Security Council, he said the reform drive
is "to make it more democratic and more representative in its
composition."
</P>
<P>
Italy, who has been seeking a membership at the Security
Council, is bidding a seat at the 15-nation body between 2001 and
2002.
</P>
<P>
"Italy is the fifth largest contributor to the U.N. budget, and
is the sixth largest contributor in terms of manpower for the U.N.
peacekeeping mission," he said. "It is sufficient for Italy from
time to time to have a seat at the Council."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
