<HEADLINE> Russian Troops Prepared for Ground Operation in Chechnya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Russian federal troops are
prepared for a ground operation in Chechnya, but it hardly makes
sense at the moment, Deputy Interior Minister Igor Zubov said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
If a political decision for a ground operation is made, the
troops are ready to carry it out, the Interfax news agency quoted
Zubov as saying at a news conference.
</P>
<P>
Following a series of deadly bombings that killed more than
300 people in Moscow and other parts of Russia and a recent
incursion of Chechen-based Islamic rebels into the southern region
of Daghestan, authorities have decided to set up a "sanitary
cordon" along the 540-kilometer border with Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
"It does not make sense to engage in a military action in the
Chechen territory. A mass intervention deep into the Chechen
republic is unfeasible," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The federal center has no plans for a mass intrusion deep
into the Chechen Republic, capturing Grozny, ousting the current
government or replacing it with a new one," Zubov said. "Such an
operation would entail numerous casualties and is hardly viable."
</P>
<P>
Zubov's remarks followed a series of media reports alleging
that the Russian military, with up to 50,000 troops on the border
with Chechnya, were planning a large scale onslaught on the region,
similar to an ill-fated operation in 1994-96 in which tens of
thousands of people died.
</P>
<P>
He described as optimal the current tactic of no direct
contact.
</P>
<P>
Federal troops will continue sealing off borders and
delivering airstrikes, including "reprisal strikes" against
militant bases, he said.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, federal planes and artillery pounded several
Chechen rebel positions in the Argun Gorge west of Kizler,
southwest of Botlikh, and near the village of Dubovskaya, Interfax
reported.
</P>
<P>
More than 100 rebels, 15 pieces of military hardware and two
arms and ammunition depots were eliminated in the raids. Federal
troops also destroyed a bridge across the Argun River to stop the
movement of rebel formations.
</P>
<P>
Zubov said the militants receive considerable foreign support
in money and mercenaries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
