<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Global Fund on Energy Resources, Environment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 22 (Xinhua) -- An international network of
non- governmental organizations, EarthAction, Wednesday called for
the creation of a global fund to finance renewable energy and the
protection of forests in developing countries.
</P>
<P>
EarthAction's international coordinator Nicholas Dunlop said
that the creation of the fund would enable developing nations to
adopt more environmentally-friendly renewable and low-carbon
energy sources such as solar and wind power to help reduce the
effects of global warming.
</P>
<P>
He said the emissions of greenhouse gases caused mainly by
burning fossil fuel, used mainly in developing countries, had
caused the atmosphere to heat more rapidly.
</P>
<P>
"Not only it is time to confront global warming head-on, it is
also time we realize that the transition to renewable energy such
as solar and wind power will create more jobs and improve our
health by giving us cleaner air, " he said.
</P>
<P>
Dunlop said one possible funding source could be a levy of a
quarter of a cent per U.S. dollar on all international currency
transactions, which if effected would generate about 200 billion
U.S. dollars a year.
</P>
<P>
"Also governments should redirect their support currently given
for fossil fuels to renewable energy and to retrain oil and coal
workers," he said.
</P>
<P>
Gas emissions would increase by 30 percent by year 2012 because
of the prevalence of fossil fuel use in most developing countries
in Africa and Latin America, he added.
</P>
<P>
Fossil fuel use in most African countries had contributed to
the depletion of forests which researchers said were losing at a
rate of 3.6 million hectares a year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
