<HEADLINE> Philippine Top Legislator Urges ASEAN Members to Enhance Inter-Parliamentary Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Philippine Senate President
Blas Ople has stressed the need for stronger bonds among the
parliaments and other lawmaking bodies of the Association of
Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN), Philippine News Agency reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Ople made the call in a speech during a dinner Tuesday at the
Manila Hotel in honor of delegates to the 20th General Assembly of
the ASEAN Inter-Parliamentary Organization (AIPO).
</P>
<P>
Earlier, in an address at the opening of the AIPO meeting last
Sunday, Ople cited the need for building strong national and
regional institutions, suggesting that the latter could help pave
the way for the setting up of an ASEAN Parliament.
</P>
<P>
"In the pursuit of self-sustaining economic growth and
stability, the values of liberty, as expressed in accountability
and transparency, are important," Ople said.
</P>
<P>
He said the principles of accountability and transparency are
best exercised through parliamentary institutions which is why
Southeast Asia needs strong parliamentary institutions.
</P>
<P>
"ASEAN needs a strong AIPO, and we need to support each other
strongly," he added.
</P>
<P>
AIPO's general assembly is composed of members of the
legislatures of ASEAN member countries. Its incumbent president is
Philippine House Speaker Manny Villar.
</P>
<P>
Attending the AIPO meeting at the Manila Hotel are 230
delegates from eight member countries, two permanent observer
countries and seven observer nations.
</P>
<P>
The assembly has just approved resolutions seeking to promote
greater regional peace and stability, speedier economic recovery,
intensified anti-drug and transnational crime prevention and
greater protection of women, children and the environment.
</P>
