<HEADLINE> India: Pak Move on Aircraft Issue "Entirely Untenable" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 22 (Xinhua) -- India said Wednesday
Pakistan's move to seek compensation for the shooting down of its
naval aircraft at the International Court of Justice (ICJ) is
"entirely untenable."
</P>
<P>
A Foreign Office spokesman said, "It is a desperate propaganda
gimmick timed to coincide with the opening of the U.N. General
Assembly in New York," adding that India will deal with it as
appropriate.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman reiterated that the Pakistani aircraft was on a
hostile military mission and was engaged in espionage activity and
committed a brazen violation of India's air space.
</P>
<P>
It had also violated the 1991 agreement between the two
countries on prevention of air space violations as well as
internationally accepted rules of engagement in such situations.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan, which has filed a case with the ICJ, has sought
compensation of 60.2 million U.S. dollars from India for the
downing of the aircraft on August 10, killing 16 navy personnel.
</P>
</TEXT>
