<HEADLINE> Nigerian Senate Leader Resorts to Interpol to Show </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABUJA, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian Senate President Evan
Enwerem has offered to submit his legal practitioner certificate
to the International Police for verification in a bid to dispel
accusation against him on falsification.
</P>
<P>
The leader of Nigeria's upper chamber of top legislature said
through his spokesman in Abuja Tuesday that the verification will
show "indeed Enwerem passed his exams for call to the English bar"
and got the document necessary to start a solicitor practice in
Britain.
</P>
<P>
The Senate president hurried back to his home country without
attending the ceremony of call to English bar, Nigeria's major
newspaper Daily Times Wednesday quoted his spokesman as saying.
</P>
<P>
But this does not mean he did not get the qualification of it,
his spokesman said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The Tell, a Lagos-based magazine, claimed in its latest issue
that Enwerem had actually forged the certificate and did not have
the qualification to start a legal practice when he came back from
Britain in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
The Senate president's spokesman also accused the magazine of
making " unlimited lies" against the third person in the country's
political hierarchy.
</P>
<P>
Enwerem has long been a target of media attacks since the
scandal of former House Speaker Ibrahim Buhari, who resigned and
was fined later due to forgery and perjury on his age and
education diploma.
</P>
<P>
Immediately after the scandal of Buhari, Enwerem was accused in
July this year by the same magazine Tell of trying to cover his
conviction of stealing in 1945 while serving as a clerk in the
British colonial administration.
</P>
<P>
But this charge was later cleared by the investigation panel of
Nigeria' s top legislature. 
</P>
</TEXT>
