<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The American Chamber of
Commerce (AmCham) and the United Nations Educational, Scientific
and Cultural Organization (UNESCO) in China have helped rebuild
three primary schools in northeast China which were destroyed in
1998 floods.
</P>
<P>
The three schools, all in Harbin city, capital of Heilongjiang
Province, have been recently renamed Hua Mei (China-USA) Primary
Schools to commemorate the 1.17 million yuan donated by AmCham (
China) members and the UNESCO Beijing representative office.
</P>
<P>
Part of the donations were used for the establishment of a 40,
000 scholarship for the schools.
</P>
<P>
Richard Latham, AmCham (China) chairman, Angus Simmons, the U.S.
Consul General in Shenyang, UNESCO officials in Beijing, and
representatives of the donor companies recently attended the
opening ceremony of one of schools, located in Xubao Town, Hulan
county.
</P>
<P>
Ian Lancasater, chairman of the AmCham (China's donation
initiative, said AmCham wishes to promote Sino-U.S. friendship
through the project and to show the responsibility of U.S. firms
to their host society.
</P>
<P>
The AmCham (China) now has 1,300 members representing 6,000 U.S.
businesses in China. 
</P>
