<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Teachers Agree in Principle to End Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's university teachers
have agreed in principle to end their nationwide strike in return
for a concession by officials to persuade the federal government
to give them an " academic allowance".
</P>
<P>
The Guardian newspaper reported Wednesday that the teachers
agreed in a communique Tuesday to "take necessary steps" towards
ending the strike which has lasted for nine days, to pave the way
for further discussions on outstanding issues.
</P>
<P>
They did not say when exactly they would return to their duty
post.
</P>
<P>
Following hours of negotiations in Abuja Tuesday with
representatives of the Academic Staff Union of Universities, the
government negotiation team announced in the communique that it
would persuade President Olusegun Obasanjo to implement the
"academic allowance."
</P>
<P>
Both parties have agreed that the purported May 25, 1998
agreement on which the union declared a trade dispute, never got
the approval of the former Head of State General Abdulsalam
Abubakar.
</P>
<P>
It was also not reflected as the outstanding commitment of the
government in the hand-over notes received by Obasanjo.
</P>
<P>
According to the communique, the review of other allowances
would commence without delay to ensure that they are accommodated
in next year's budget.
</P>
<P>
However, the teachers union was asked to note that whereas its
members in state universities are also involved in the on-going
strike, "the federal government team cannot make commitments on
behalf of state governments."
</P>
<P>
It further stated that the on-going trade dispute declared by
the union undermined the government's "serious" concern to
implement far-reaching programs to revitalize tertiary
institutions in the country.
</P>
<P>
The communique said that the current negotiation "will
certainly go beyond the issue of staff welfare and allowances,
and will address other aspects of the problems of higher
institutions in the country and those of other unions with similar
interests."
</P>
<P>
The Academic Staff Union of Universities embarked on a strike
action last Monday, insisting that the federal government must
implement the agreement that it allegedly had reached with the
former military administration.
</P>
<P>
The agreement in question was to specifically increase the
allowances of university teachers by two billion naira (one U.S.
dollar equals some 100 naira), made up of 500-million-naira
academic allowances and 1.5-billion- naira recoverable loans to
both academic and non-academic staff. 
</P>
</TEXT>
