<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Trade Surplus Falls in August </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The surplus plunged to 689.4 billion yen (5.9 billion dollars)
as a stronger yen held back exports, the ministry said in a
preliminary report.
</P>
<P>
Exports dropped 6.9 percent to 3,736.7 billion yen (32.2
billion dollars), as the yen's value was steeply higher in terms
of the U.S. dollar than a year before.
</P>
<P>
The stronger yen propelled shipments of steel, office equipment
and automobiles to contract by 25.1 percent, 16.4 percent and 6.9
percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
Imports also retreated 2.4 percent to 3,047.3 billion yen (26.3
billion dollars), with imports of aircraft and coal down 66.3
percent and 28.0 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
Japan's merchandise trade balance is measured on the basis of
goods clearing customs and is reported before adjustment for
seasonal factors.
</P>
<P>
The yen traded at an average of 115.91 yen in August, a 23.8
percent rise from the 143.48 yen a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
Japan's politically sensitive trade surplus with the United
States climbed 24.3 percent to 534.4 billion yen (4.6 billion
dollars), marking the fourth straight month of expansion.
</P>
<P>
The trade surplus with other Asian countries fell 4.6 percent,
while that with the 15-member European Union posted a 27.0 percent
decrease, the ministry said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
