<HEADLINE> Russian Planes Pound Rebels in Chechnya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Russian federal planes and
artillery delivered strikes on Chechen rebels Tuesday, the
Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Rebels "suffered serious losses" in the raids on positions in
the Argun Gorge west of Kizlyar, southwest of Botlikh, and near
the village of Dubovskaya, Interfax said, quoting regional
headquarters for federal troops in the North Caucasus.
</P>
<P>
More than 100 rebels, 15 pieces of military hardware, and two
arms and ammunition depots were eliminated. Federal planes also
destroyed a bridge across the Argun River to prevent the movement
of rebel formations, Interfax said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Russian federal units in Daghestan continue to
strengthen their defense system along the administrative border
with Chechnya amid reports that Chechen rebels are planning new
incursions into the southern republic.
</P>
<P>
The rebels have launched two waves of assaults on Daghestan
from the breakaway province Chechnya since early August. In both
cases, they were driven out by federal troops and local forces.
</P>
<P>
The Russian Interior Ministry said Wednesday that search
investigation operations continue in Daghestan's Buinaksk district,
where policemen, interior troops and volunteers are carrying out
mop-up operations in the forests and mountain slopes near the
villages of Chabanmakhi and Karamakhi, and along various possible
retreat routes of the rebels.
</P>
<P>
In another related development, the Russian Defense Ministry
said Wednesday that a visit by Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev to
Switzerland, scheduled for September 23-25, has been canceled as
the result of a "difficult political situation in the country and
the continuing operations of federal troops against illegal armed
groups in the North Caucasus region," the Itar-Tass reported.
</P>
