<HEADLINE> ECOMOG Warns S. Leone Rebels Against Arms Seizure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian-led west African
peace- keeping force ECOMOG has threatened to discard the current
cease-fire regime in Sierra Leone, Nigeria's Guardian newspaper
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The ECOMOG said it would do that if the country's former
rebels refuse to return the ammunition they stole from a
contingent of the force.
</P>
<P>
"My troops will violate the cease-fire if our ammunition seized
by rebels are not retrieved within a week," Commander of the
Guinean contingent of the ECOMOG Haji Kante was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The ECOMOG confirmed Tuesday that the Guinean troops were
heading home through rebel-controlled areas when their arms were
seized days ago.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG spokesman Chris Olukolade said that the Revolutionary
United Front (RUF) rebels stole the weapons and temporarily
abducted several Guinean ECOMOG soldiers along the Mange-Kambia
highway, north of the Freetown peninsula.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman disclosed that the ECOMOG was in contact with the
RUF leadership and that he hoped the situation could be resolved.
</P>
<P>
A cease-fire was reached in Sierra Leone in May between the S.
Leone government, the ECOMOG force protecting it and the RUF. A
peace accord signed in Togolese capital Lome in July followed the
cease-fire, ending the country's nine-year civil war. 
</P>
