<DOCNO> XIE19990922.0140 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Somali Refugees Flock to Gulf Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The fierce fightings in
southern Somalia have been seriously felt in the northeastern
region, with refugees continuously storming into the port town of
Bossaso to ride vessels for the Gulf countries.
</P>
<P>
In coping with the new influx of people trying to travel
illegally to the Gulf countries, the Puntland administration has
taken serious measures against those illegal facilitators of the
terribly dangerous adventure to Yemen on boats.
</P>
<P>
In a campaign ordered by the police commissioner of Bossaso,
more than 70 people trying to travel on those illegal boats have
been rounded up in the past two days.
</P>
<P>
According to reports reaching here, the administration has
forcefully closed down 12 offices engaged in arranging illegal
trip to the Gulf countries, with five people apprehended and taken
to the police custody.
</P>
<P>
The administration has also caught two of the boats trying to
smuggle the Somali refugees into the Gulf countries through Yemen.
</P>
<P>
Despite the efforts by the Puntland administration against
illegal and dangerous travel, many Somali adventurers still sailed
through the Red Sea towards Yemen.
</P>
<P>
It is not yet known what the Puntland authorities are going to
do about the ordinary citizens who are merely fleeing the
prolonged civil war and droughts.
</P>
<P>
However, the facilitators of the illegal adventure through the
Red Sea together with the navigators of their boats are more
likely to face punitive measures such as fines and imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
The police of Bossaso have also foiled attempts of exporting
coal to the Gulf countries on similar boats. Several lorries
transporting the stock towards the ports of Bossaso region have
been halted.
</P>
<P>
Several hundred people are known to have died after those
poorly maintained boats capsized in the middle of the sea in the
past three years.
</P>
<P>
But quite a lot of other people are known to have lost their
lives after the men navigating the boats ordered them to get down
before reaching the Yemen sea-shores for fear of the authorities
there.
</P>
<P>
Most of those resorting to the adventure through Bossaso come
from the war ravaged areas of southern Somalia including
Mogadishu, Bay, Middle and Lower Jubba regions.
</P>
<P>
The minority communities best known as Rer Hamar, Bravana and
Jarer, were those who first opened the way to Saudi Arabia through
Yemen in the early years of the civil war.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
