<DOCNO> XIE19990922.0141 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Firm Develops Eco-friendly Packaging </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 22 (Xinhua) -- An Israeli firm affiliated
with the Technion Institute of Technology has developed a cheap
packaging material which self-destructs instead of polluting the
environment.
</P>
<P>
The Haifa-based mini-startup company, called Rademate
Ltd. announced in a press release Wednesday that the company's new
packaging material is as strong and water-resistant as plastic
but completely biodegradable in the ground or at garbage site.
</P>
<P>
The rapid biodegradable hydrophobic material (RBHM) can be
recycled and serve as alternative to plastic trash and it can be
used to coat cellulose-based products, such as paper and
cardboard, making them strong and water-resistant like plastic,
the company said.
</P>
<P>
The material is based on pulp and is combined with polymer
compounds, making the cellulose base behave like a biological
material and decompose due to enzymatic activity in the ground.
</P>
<P>
Unlike plastic, which lasts almost forever, the new material
can be recycled, and whatever is left decomposes in two or three
months at the garbage dump. It is also much cheaper than other
biodegradable material developed by polymer manufactures in the
United States and Europe.
</P>
<P>
It can be also manufactured with existing equipment used by
paper and pulp industry, the company added.
</P>
<P>
Among the products for which it can be used are garbage bags,
packaging materials for chemical and fertilizers, disposable pots
and compositing bags, disposable cups and plates and diapers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990922.0142 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> an epitome of China's achievements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
After his latest trip to that city, he wrote a story about
Shanghai's present mayor Xu Kuangdi, which appeared in Tuesday's "
South China Morning Post," a major English newspaper here.
</P>
<P>
"His focus is to raise the overall quality of life of the
people and the cultural civilization of the city," Sinclair wrote.
</P>
<P>
"Within a short stroll from the imposing granite municipal
headquarters of the City Hall is the splendid opera house, the
magnificent museum, the city planning exhibition hall," he
described the city in his story. "All are new. All are among the
gems -- along with vast sporting stadiums, a glittering convention
center in Pudong, a stunning array of new hotels and an emerging
sophisticated cafe society that make Shanghai with its historic
mystique a booming tourist destination," he wrote.
</P>
<P>
"This is a consequence of his (Xu Kuangdi's) major task of
harmonizing economic development with environmental protection,"
noted Sinclair in his story.
</P>
<P>
In 1988, Sinclair met the then Shanghai Mayor Zhu Rongji, who
later became the premier of China.
</P>
<P>
"What Zhu told me to be done in Shanghai at that time has come
true today," said Sinclair in an exclusive interview with Xinhua
on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In the story, Sinclair told his readers how Zhu tried his best
to improve the investment environment in Shanghai and to guarantee
that foreign enterprises could do business there in accordance
with international practices.
</P>
<P>
During that trip to Shanghai, Sinclair even went to a number of
toilets in the city to see whether they were as clean as Zhu had
ordered to keep. He found they were all reasonably hygienic.
</P>
<P>
In June 1992, Sinclair became the first foreign reporter to
interview Zhu's successor, Huang Ju.
</P>
<P>
During the lengthy interview, Huang talked about his vision of
a new Shanghai without destroying the old one. "The past (of
Shanghai) will be remembered on one bank of the (Huangpu) river.
The future will rise o the other," Sinclair quoted Huang as saying.
</P>
<P>
The development of Shanghai is only part of the achievements
made in China in the past decades, Sinclair said.
</P>
<P>
The reform and opening up policy has been proven successful so
far and it is the right direction for the development of China in
the future, Sinclair commented.
</P>
<P>
Education is one of China's greatest achievements made in the
past 50 years, Kevin Sinclair said, citing the successful
popularization of the common spoken Chinese, Putonghua, in the
whole nation.
</P>
<P>
On another front, Sinclair said that China has fed the biggest
population in the world and has successfully implemented the
policy of family planning, adding that the equality between men
and women in China is also impressive.
</P>
<P>
Having got his permanent identification card of the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) shortly after Hong Kong's
handover, Sinclair now considers himself a Hongkonger, and that's
not without a reason.
</P>
<P>
Kevin Sinclair has been working in this city for more than 30
years after he arrived here in 1963 from New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
He and his American wife Kit frequently visit China's mainland.
Kit is an assistant professor of the Hong Kong Polytechnic
University. She also teaches in several universities and colleges
in the mainland.
</P>
<P>
Sinclair said he writes some 12 stories a week about Hong Kong
and China's mainland, contributing stories to many newspapers and
magazines.
</P>
<P>
Sinclair said that the "village elections" in China have
impressed him very much.
</P>
<P>
"The elections have been successful," he said. "They showed
that people want to have a say in the way they live. " Villagers
could vote back or vote out officials, depending on whether or not
they did a good job for the people, he said.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on China's Hong Kong policy, Sinclair said that
China has done everything it promised to do in the agreements of
1984 and later.
</P>
<P>
"I think Hong Kong would have been in a very difficult economic
situation over the past two years without the full backing of the
Chinese government," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
