<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic
briefs from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- Petroleum India International (PII), a consortium
of 10 Indian public sector petroleum and petrochemical companies,
will soon open offices in the United Arab Emirates (UAE) to offer
training programs and expertise to clients in the region.
</P>
<P>
The consortium is the only single window organization in India
to render technical, managerial, human resources and training
services in the upstream as well as downstream petroleum sector
on a global basis, said the Khaleej Times daily on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
PII has been active in 15 countries, mostly in the Middle
East. It will locate its two UAE offices in Abu Dhabi and
Dubai.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- Obeid Bin Saif Al Nasir, Minister of Petroleum and
Mineral Resources of the Untied Arab Emirates (UAE), left here
Wednesday for Vienna, Austria, to attend the 108th ministerial
meeting of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries
(OPEC).
</P>
<P>
The meeting, which starts later Wednesday, will discuss a host
of issues concerning the oil industry and market, as well as the
election of a new secretary general for the organization.
</P>
<P>
RIYADH -- The Saudi Arabian Agricultural Bank offered a
total of 1.123 billion rials (299.5 million dollars) in loans and
grants-in-aid to Saudi farmers last year.
</P>
<P>
The loans were extended to 5,607 beneficiaries, at a total
value of 897.3 million rials (239.3 million dollars) to share with
farmers the cost of agricultural tools, machinery, irrigation
pumps, drilling of wells, purchase of seeds, fuel and
insecticides.
</P>
<P>
The money also financed some rural projects such as the raising
of poultry, planting of palm trees, cultivation of vegetables and
fruits, dairy product factories, erection of green houses and
building of fishing boats.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The Misr (Egypt) company for petroleum industry has
received 15 offers from international companies specialized in
water and electric power generating to implement a project in Suez
city with a total investment of over 750 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Four companies from Germany, South Korea, France are competing
for the construction of a 300-megavolt electric power generating
plant while another 11 companies are offering to build the water
station to produce the required steam for the project, the Alam Al
Yom daily reported Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
