<HEADLINE> Multimedia Asia '99 Opens in Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The Multimedia Asia '99
(MMA '99) opened at the Mines city near here Wednesday with an aim
to promote the Multimedia Super Corridor (MSC) in Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
The five-day conference-cum-exhibition is being attended by
local and foreign figures prominent in the information technology
industry, who had an opportunity to have a dialogue with Prime
Minister Mahathir Mohamad Wednesday evening.
</P>
<P>
During the dialogue, Mahathir said developing the agricultural
sector and turning the country into a food producer may be his
next vision for Malaysia after the MSC.
</P>
<P>
The MSC is a 50 by 15 square kilometer zone stretching
southwards from here designated as a hub for the development of
multimedia products and services.
</P>
<P>
As it was, Malaysia was importing too much food items, which
accounted for a large chunk of the country's import bills that
burdened the government especially during the economic downturn,
he said.
</P>
<P>
"My next vision may be more mundane than the previous one but
not less useful...we can't be importing too much food," Mahathir
said when a participant at the Multimedia Asia '99 conference and
exhibition asked him about his new vision.
</P>
<P>
Turning to the MSC, Mahathir said like many other Malaysian
endeavors, the MSC would be successful.
</P>
<P>
The MMA '99, the fourth consecutive one which positions the MSC
as an important hub in the network of dialogue partners, was
themed "Re-aligning for A New Economy" this year.
</P>
<P>
In conjunction with the MMA '99 organized by Malaysia's
National Information Technology Council (NITC) in association with
the Multimedia Development Corporation, an exhibition would be
held at the Mines city from September 23 to 26.
</P>
<P>
Some 150 local and foreign companies are participating in the
exhibition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
