<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Full Text of Communique of 4th Plenum of CPC Central Committee (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The following is the full
text of a communique from the 4th Plenary Session of the 15th
Central Committee of the Communist Party of China (CPC).
</P>
<P>
Communique of the 4th Plenary Session of the 15th Central
Committee of the Communist Party of China
</P>
<P>
(September 22, 1999)
</P>
<P>
The 4th Plenary Session of the 15th Central Committee of the
Communist Party of China was held in Beijing, September 19-22,
1999.
</P>
<P>
Attending the plenum were 189 members of the CPC Central
Committee and 147 alternate members of the Central Committee.
Members of the Standing Committee of the CPC Central Commission
for Discipline Inspection of the CPC and leading officials of
departments concerned also attended as observers.
</P>
<P>
The session was presided over by the Political Bureau of the
CPC Central Committee. Jiang Zemin, general secretary of the CPC
Central Committee, made an important speech at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Those attending the plenary session discussed and approved the
CPC Central Committee Decision on Issues Related to State-Owned
Enterprise Reforms and Development. The plenum held that pushing
reforms and development of State-owned enterprises forward is an
important and urgent task. State-owned enterprises are a pillar of
the national economy. To fulfill the country's cross-century
development tasks as defined at the 15th Congress of the CPC
Central Committee, establish and develop a socialist market
economic system, and maintain the sustained, rapid, and sound
development of the national economy, it is imperative that the
restructuring of State-owned enterprises, the transforming of
their management, the adjustment of their structure, and the
advancement of their technology be vigorously promoted. The
reforms and development in State-owned enterprises have reached a
crucial stage and some deeply-rooted problems need to be dealt
with. It is therefore a timely and necessary endeavor for the
plenary session to focus on issues related to State-owned
enterprises.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990922.0159 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Full Text of Communique of 4th Plenum of CPC Central Committee (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Those attending the plenary session spoke highly of the role of
State-owned enterprises in the country's economic and social
development and in the socialist system. They reached a consensus
that in the 50 years since the founding of the New China,
especially since the beginning of reforms and opening-up, the
Party has led all nationalities of the country in the unceasing
struggle to turn China from a backward, poor agricultural country
into a socialist one that is becoming a much better-off society
and moving toward the goal of industrialization and modernization.
This is a great historic leap forward in the course of developing
the Chinese nation, and State-owned enterprises and the working
class have made an indelible contribution. To increase the
economic and defense strength and the national cohesion of the
country in the midst of fierce global competition at the turn of
the century, no time can be lost in pushing the restructuring and
development of State-owned enterprises forward and in helping
strengthen the State sector of the economy and allowing it to
assume its major role in the nation's economy.
</P>
<P>
Those attending the plenary session decided the major
objectives and guiding principles for the reforms and development
of State-owned enterprises until the year 2010. They emphasized
that, in fulfilling this historic task, every effort must be made
first of all in realizing the three-year goal getting State-owned
enterprises out of difficulties through the reforms. Key sectors,
enterprises, and old industrial centers need to be better managed
in accordance with the realities of different sectors and areas
and the process of unbalanced development, and solutions to major
problems at present need to be combined with long-term development,
and favorable conditions for the development of State-owned
enterprises across the century need to be created.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990922.0160 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Discipline Commission Explains Senior Party Official Bribery Case ( 1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The Communist Party of China'
s Central Commission for Discipline Inspection suggested to the
4th plenary session of the 15th CPC Central Committee that Xu
Yunhong be dismissed form his post as alternate member of the CPC
Central Committee.
</P>
<P>
The Central Commission for Discipline Inspection also suggested
that Xu be expelled from the Party in accordance with the CPC
constitution and discipline regulations and that he be removed
from his position as deputy to the Ningbo City People's Congress
and Zhejiang Provincial People's Congress according to legal
procedures.
</P>
<P>
Xu was formerly also a standing committee member of the
Zhejiang Provincial CPC Committee and Ningbo City Party Committee
Secretary.
</P>
<P>
Xu is suspected of violating the criminal law and judicial
departments will review his case according to law.
</P>
<P>
The Central Commission for Discipline Inspection reviewed Xu's
case and found that, after being asked by his son, he had helped a
business office of a Ningbo trust and investment company obtain
the qualifications for independent fund-raising.
</P>
<P>
Xu's son received money and goods worth more than 900,000 yuan
(108,000 U.S. dollars) from the general manager of the company
office in return.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990922.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Aftershocks Rock Nantou of Taiwan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 22 (Xinhua)-- An aftershock, measuring 6.7
on the Richter scale, rocked east of Nantou, central Taiwan
province, at 08:14 (Beijing time).
</P>
<P>
The epicenter was at 24 north latitude and 121 east longitude,
according to China's seismological networks.
</P>
<P>
The aftershock was followed by another one 35 minutes later at
the area of Tuesday's killer quake, measuring 6.2 on the Richter
scale.
</P>
<P>
It is learned that the two tremors were felt in parts of Fujian,
Guangdong, Zhejiang and Jiangxi provinces, particularly in Fujian
Province.
</P>
<P>
Between 04:02 and 15:06 Tuesday, one aftershock, measuring 6 to
6.9, and two, measuring between 5 and 5.9, jolted the quake-
stricken area again.
</P>
<P>
Latest reports say that Tuesday's earthquake in Taiwan killed
more than 1,700 people, injured about 4,000, trapped nearly 3,000
in the rubbles, and left another 216 missing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
