<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Shares Dive to Month Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Singapore Shares dived to a
month-low Wednesday as the market sentiment was dampened by the
overnight sharp drop on Wall Street and affected by Bank of
Japan's decision to keep its monetary policy unchanged.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark Straits Times Index (STI) plunged 46.44 points to
end at 2,062.60 points in fairly active dealings.
</P>
<P>
The total turnover increased to 228.57 million units valued at
544.76 million Singapore dollars (about 319.30 million U.S.
dollars). Decliners outstripped advancers by 270 to 43 with 137
counters unchanged.
</P>
<P>
AsianMicro topped the volume list as 43.46 million units of the
stock changed hands. Gen Int was the second most heavily traded
share with a turnover of 16.04 million shares. SingTel registered
a volume of 10.59 million counters.
</P>
<P>
YHS led the gainers of the day rising by 30 cents to close at
6.00 Singapore dollars. Seaview moved up 20 cents to finish at
10.80 Singapore dollars. C&AMP;C edged up 15 cents to end at 6.00
Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, SPH headed the descent of the day as it
dropped 130 cents to close at 27.70 Singapore dollars. SPH 100
lost 120 cents to finish at 27.60 Singapore dollars. SIA 200 sank
110 cents to end at 16.80 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
Dealers attributed the day's slump to the overnight sharp fall
on Wall Street and the adverse effect of Bank of Japan's move to
maintain its monetary stance.
</P>
<P>
They said Bank of Japan's decision to keep its monetary policy
unchanged disappointed the market which was anticipating concrete
moves to reverse the sustained strength of the yen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
