<DOCNO> XIE19990922.0166 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Discipline Commission Explains Senior Party Official Bribery Case ( 2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
With Xu's support and connivance, the company's business office
general manager violated management regulations and his acts of
embezzlement and bribery failed to be investigated and prosecuted
timely, causing assets losses worth 1.197 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
In response to his son's request, Xu ordered Ningbo Daily to
purchase the Huahong International Center building, which is of
poor quality.
</P>
<P>
The building's owner gave Xu's son money and goods worth more
than 2 million yuan in return. At Xu's wife's request, Xu also
helped a Ningbo company get 25.67 million yuan and 5.4 million U.S.
dollars worth of loans. The general manager of the company gave Xu
's wife more than 4 million yuan in return. The company now can
not afford to pay back the loans.
</P>
<P>
The Standing Committee of the Central Commission for Discipline
Inspection said that, as a senior Party official, Xu took
advantage of his post and repeatedly responded to his wife's and
his son's requests for personal return. His wife and son received
a large amount of money and goods in return.
</P>
<P>
The standing committee of the commission believes that the acts
caused serious economic losses for the Party and the State and
caused very bad political influence and it said that Xu's actions
were a serious violation of Party disciplines and that Xu is not
qualified to be a Party member.
</P>
<P>
Some of Xu's actions may have violated the criminal law and
they will be dealt with by the judiciary.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990922.0167 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Full Text of Communique of 4th Plenum of CPC Central Committee (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
It was pointed out at the plenum that the strategic adjustment
of the layout of the State sector of the economy needs to be
combined with optimization of and improvements in the industrial
and ownership structure, sticking to advancement in some areas and
retrenchment in others and refraining from some things in order to
do others, so as to increase the ability of the State sector to
control the economy. The State sector needs to be given a dominant
position in important industries and key sectors that are closely
related to the national economic lifeline, while in other
industries and sectors the effort should be concentrated on
improving the overall quality of the economy by means of capital
restructuring and structural adjustments. Effective methods of
public ownership must be explored, a joint stock system and mixed
forms of ownership developed vigorously, and major enterprises
held by the State. A continuous effort needs to be made in the
strategic restructuring of State-owned enterprises, making full
use of the market mechanism, vigorously developing large
enterprises and enterprise groups, and relaxing controls over mid-
sized and small State-owned enterprises to breathe more life into
them. The role of other mid-sized and small enterprises needs to
be brought into play in promoting social and economic development,
and efforts need to be made to actively support science and
technology businesses, and develop service systems for mid-sized
and small enterprises. The State needs to increase support for
adjusting the distribution of industry and reorganizing
enterprises in old industrial bases, the central and western parts
of the country and areas inhabited by ethnic groups.
</P>
<P>
Those attending the plenum pointed out that a modern enterprise
system is the orientation of State-owned enterprise reforms and an
effective way to combine public ownership with a market economy.
The separation of government functions from enterprise management
needs to be continued and effective forms of State assets
management explored under a principle of State ownership,
management at different levels, authorized operation, and
supervision based on division of labor. Large and mid-sized State-
owned enterprises should carry out reforms in accordance with the
standards of the corporate system, establish a better corporate
management structure, and gear their operation systems to the
market. They should establish an income distribution system that
conforms to the modern enterprise system and provide effective
incentive and restraints. There needs to be a concrete emphasis on
strengthening enterprise management, studying development
strategies, perfecting rules and regulations, strengthening weak
links, adopting modern management skills, methods and means, and
increasing economic gains.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
