<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia's GDP Growth Lower Than Projected </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Zambia's Gross Domestic
Product (GDP) this year will only grow by just over one percent,
lower than the projected four percent because of a decline in
output in the mining, quarrying and construction sectors.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary data indicate that the decline in the expected
economic growth has largely been caused by the operational
problems at the Zambia Consolidated Copper Mines (ZCCM) which has
adversely affected the mining and quarrying sectors, Times of
Zambia newspaper Wednesday quoted the Bank of Zambia senior
economist Jacob Lushinga as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said, however, substantial economic growth is expected in
the agricultural sector.
</P>
<P>
The agricultural sector estimated to grow by six percent this
year is expected to contribute a large portion to the growth of
the GDP, he added.
</P>
<P>
Other areas expected to record positive growth include the
sectors of manufacturing, power and services, he said.
</P>
<P>
According to Lushinga, the increase in prices of petroleum
products and electricity tariffs between April and July is the
main cause for the rise in inflation rates.
</P>
<P>
On the Balance of Payments, Lushinga said preliminary estimates
showed that the position improved to a surplus of 36.2 million
U.S. dollars in the second quarter against a deficit of 22.2
million dollars recorded in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
And the economic activity for this year is expected to face
many challenges like high inflation rates emanating from expected
oil price and electricity tariff hikes and a further delay in
disposing of the remaining units of ZCCM, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
