<HEADLINE> Arson Destroys Aircraft in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 22 (Xinhua) -- A mysterious fire has reduced
a light aircraft to debris at a airport in the suburb of the
Kenyan capital Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
Arsonists sneaked into the Wilson Airport at 2 a.m. Tuesday and
used explosives to blow up the 14-seat aircraft worth 1.4 million
U.S. dollars, according to airport authorities.
</P>
<P>
The aircraft was set ablaze in the parking area, just 15 meters
from the airport's main gate, Daily Nation reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The police immediately launched investigations to uncover who
was behind the incident.
</P>
<P>
The plane was reportedly at the center of a legal case between
three family members of the late North Eastern Province chief
Abdulahi Ahmed.
</P>
<P>
On September 15, a justice at a commercial court gave an order
to ground the aircraft at the airport until the dispute was
resolved.
</P>
<P>
The plane used to fly on a weekly basis between Nairobi and
Somalia. 
</P>
