<HEADLINE> Chinese Resolution On Fighting Corruption </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 22 (Xinhua)-- China's Supreme People's
Procuratorate will have a resolution on dealing with corruption to
push forward the nation's campaign against bribery and
embezzlement, Zhao Dengju, deputy procurator-general of the SPP,
told a national conference on anti-corruption here today.
</P>
<P>
The resolution's purpose is to standardize investigation
procedures and to perfect the prosecuting mechanism to improve the
case-handling ability of people's procuratorates, Zhao said.
</P>
<P>
China's corruption work has made some progress in quest for
justice and openness, Zhao said, and procuratorates nationwide
have dealt with a great number of corruption cases. Since 1997,
people's procuratorates' anti-corruption departments have dealt
with more than 103,000 bribery and embezzlement cases, arrested
some 115,000 suspects, and recovered 10 billion yuan worth of lost
property.
</P>
<P>
But, even with the achievements, the group charged with
fighting corruption faces challenges. For example, some
prosecutors are not really qualified and cannot adapt to the
changing situation, Zhao pointed out. He asked all prosecutors to
make a greater effort in the fight against corruption to create a
healthier, long-lasting corruption-free society. 
</P>
</TEXT>
