<DOCNO> XIE19990922.0195 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Population to Hit Six Billion: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The world population will
hit six billion on October 12, doubling since 1960 and an increase
of one billion people in just 12 years, according to a report
issued here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The report entitled "The State of World Population, 1999"
prepared by the United Nations Population Fund (UNFPA) said global
population is rising by about 78 million people a year, although
the growth rate has slowed from 2.4 to 1.3 percent in the past 30
years.
</P>
<P>
The report projects that world population will grow from the
current 6 billion to between 7.3 and 10.7 billion by 2050, with
8.9 billion considered the most likely. This means that the world
population may grow almost as much in the next 50 years as in the
past 50 years, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The report said that over 95 percent of the growth is taking
place in the world's poorest and least-prepared countries, such as
sub-Saharan Africa, parts of South Asia and Western Asia. In
Sub-Saharan Africa, the average woman has 5.5 children.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, population growth has slowed or stopped in Europe,
North America and Japan, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The united States is the only industrial country where large
population increases are still projected, largely as the result of
immigration, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Due to improved education and health care and increased access
to family planning in Asia, Africa and Latin America, birth rates
in developing countries have dropped from six children per woman
in 1969 to under three today.
</P>
<P>
However, the report said, the regions and countries with high
birth rate also have more young people. In 62 countries in Africa,
Asia and Latin America, over 40 percent of the population is under
age 15.
Presenting a bleak picture in the developing countries, it said
over one billion people are still deprived of basic needs and, of
the 4.8 billion people in developing countries, nearly three
fifths lack basic sanitation, almost a third have no access to
clean water, a quarter do not have adequate housing and a fifth
have no access to modern health services, a fifth of children do
not attend school to grade 5.
</P>
<P>
UNFPA presents a report on the state of world population every
year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990922.0196 </DOCNO>
