<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Volcano Activity "Worrisome:" Phivolcs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Mayon Volcano in the southern
Philippines belched off ashes for four minutes shortly before noon
Wednesday, the Philippine Institute of Volcanology and Seismology
(Phivolcs) said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the explosion, a quake of high-frequency and a tremor
of short duration were detected in the 24-hour period, Phivolcs
said in a bulletin.
</P>
<P>
while describing the activity as "worrisome" and warning people
to stay away from the Permanent Danger Zone (PDZ) of the volcano,
the institute said it was a "weak to wispy steaming" off. Sulfuric
acid flux was measured at 1,740 tons as of Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Experts said extra precaution must be specially taken by
residents along the Bonga Gully on the southeast sector of the
volcano.
</P>
<P>
The current alert level is maintained at 2, which means
volcanoes show "unrest of probably magnetic origin and could
eventually lead to eruption."
</P>
<P>
Ernesto Corpuz of Phivolcs said despite today's low-level
alert, Mayon's recent "closely-spaced eruptions" could be a cause
for worry, for these could suddenly lead to a "full explosion."
</P>
<P>
The highest seismic level at Phivolcs is 5, a "hazardous" or
"full explosion," such as when Mayon exploded in April 1993 and
caused 70 deaths in the PDZ, Corpuz added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
