<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 09:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Blames U.S., British Envoys for Blocking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Iraq's Health Ministry on
Wednesday blamed the U.S. and British governments for delaying
the approval of 24 medical contracts it signed with foreign
companies.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the ministry criticized the U.S. and British
representatives at the U.N. Sanctions Committee for fabricating
lies and excuses to prevent supplying Iraq with medicine and
medical appliances.
</P>
<P>
These blocked contracts were concluded in the previous phases
of the oil-for-food program under sums allocated for the health
sector, he said.
</P>
<P>
He elaborated that 15 percent of the contracts of the
first phase of the deal has not been shipped yet despite the
elapse of three years after they were concluded.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, he added that still put on hold under flimsy pretexts
are four contracts worth 1.7 million U.S. dollars of the second
phase, two contracts valued at 2.4 million dollars of the fourth
phase and 18 contracts of the fifth phase worth 44 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Under the oil-for-food deal, now in its sixth phase which
expires in November, Iraq is allowed to export limited amount of
oil in every six months to buy food, medicine and other
humanitarian supplies for its 24 million people.
</P>
<P>
Since the fourth phase of the deal, the ceiling of the
amount of oil Iraq is allowed to sell has been raised to
5.2 billion dollars from 2 billion dollars for the first three
phases.
</P>
<P>
Baghdad has long accused the U.S. and British envoys at
the Sanctions Committee of hampering the endorsement of its
contracts, arguing that the oil-for-food deal has failed to
alleviate the suffering of the Iraqi people.
</P>
<P>
According to a report of the United Nations' Children Fund
(UNICEF), mortality rates among Iraqi children have more than
doubled since the imposition of the U.N. sanctions on Iraq in
1990.
</P>
<P>
Iraq's Health Ministry announced on Sunday that nearly 8,000
Iraqi children aged under five died in last August of
various curable diseases and malnutrition due to the continuation
of the nine-year-old embargo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
