<HEADLINE> El Al Delays Decision to Choose Between Boeing, Airbus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Israel's national airliner
El Al has delayed a decision on from which of the two biggest
aircraft manufacturers in the world to purchase new planes in the
coming years, local media reports said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The reports quoted El Al Director-General Joseph Ciechanover
as saying that his company is seeking for specific proposals from
the U.S.-based Boeing and the France-based Airbus for the deal,
which is estimated at some 350 million to 400 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
An El Al spokesman said the Israeli airline wants to obtain
commitments from Boeing and Airbus concerning subsequent deals
that will result from the upcoming arrangement.
</P>
<P>
The decision will be postponed from Wednesday until next week,
the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Vying for the contract, both Boeing and Airbus have sent their
top executives to Israel in the last two months.
</P>
<P>
Boeing is trying to sell three 777s to El Al, offering to buy
back some of its 757s previously sold to this 38-year customer.
</P>
<P>
Airbus is offering El Al two A340 and two A330 planes,
promising to pump back roughly 150 million dollars in offset
purchases.
</P>
<P>
El Al currently operates an all-Boeing fleet and the Israeli
government is a key customer for Boeing's military
business. Boeing triumphed against Airbus in El Al's last tender
in December 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
