<HEADLINE> Over 1,000 Participants Expected for Maritime </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, September 22 (Xinhua) -- More than 1,000 participants
from 35 countries will attend "Maritime Cyprus '99", a major
conference on shipping, to be held on October 3-6, the Cyprus Mail
newspaper reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The conference, with the theme of "Shipping in the Dawn of a
New Century," is organized by Cyprus' government in cooperation
with the Central Bank of Cyprus and the Cyprus Shipping Council,
a private shipping institution.
</P>
<P>
The conference will focus on the latest developments in
shipping industry in the European Union (EU), ship finance,
shipbrokering, the policy of international organizations of both
workers in the shipping industry and shipowners, and the
prospects of the shipping markets.
</P>
<P>
The list of speakers includes Williams O'Neil, Secretary
General of the International Maritime Organization (IMO), and
George Vassiliou, Cyprus' chief negotiator in the island's
accession talks with the EU.
</P>
<P>
Permanent Secretary of Cyprus' Communications and Works
Ministry Vassos Pyrgos told the press on Tuesday that over the
past few years Cyprus had worked hard to upgrade the image and
the quality of its fleet.
</P>
<P>
"A lot has been done also in the prevention of sea pollution
and the improvement of working conditions on Cyprus ships, which
creates hope for higher standards of safety," he added.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus ranks the sixth on the list of maritime countries, with
2,667 vessels and 26.5 million gross tons.
</P>
<P>
A total of 120 accidents happened in 1998 involving
Cyprus-flagged ships, which resulted in the deaths of 28 people and
the loss of five ships.
</P>
<P>
So far this year, there have been 53 accidents, which resulted
in the deaths of nine people and the loss of three ships. 
</P>
</TEXT>
