<HEADLINE> Camels into Chinese Capital for National Ethnic Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 22 (Xinhua) -- With most part of an expected
field of 4,500 athletes checked-in in various Beijing hotels for
China's Sixth National Games of Traditional Ethnic Sports opening
on Friday, there are some unusual arrivals.
</P>
<P>
Camels, 12 of them, have being warming up in a horse racing
track in a northeastern Beijing suburb since Monday, for a
demonstration race at the week-long National Games here.
</P>
<P>
The giant and usually tame animals were used for transportation
to and from Beijing a long time ago. But now only in the Zoo can
Beijing kids have a closer look of the friendly animals.
</P>
<P>
The camels were hand-picked from Alxa and Bayannur Leagues in
the Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region near China's northern border.
</P>
<P>
"They must be smart, strong and, of course, tame,"
Qinggelebayer, coach of the Alxa League camel racing team, said of
how they were chosen.
</P>
<P>
"The herdsmen in our League were very eager to show up with
their livestock and have them picked up, feeling proud of the
honor of showing them at the National Games. But we only need six,
" said the 49-year-old official of the League's farming and animal
husbandry bureau. The six others were picked up from neiboring
Bayannur League and are scheduled to be here later Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"They are really smart, aren't they?" proudly asked
Qinggelebayer, a veterinarian himself and a participant of the
past three National Games.
</P>
<P>
The camels were then transported aboard a truck more than 1,600
kilometers eastward to the Chinese capital. "48 hard hours, with
heavy rains for some 36 hours," he recalled. "We are lucky they (
camels) didn't catch cold," he said, all smiles.
</P>
<P>
"The weather in Beijing is nice and our camels go around very
well. The riders are now trying to decorate them up so as to
present a more attractive show at the Games."
</P>
<P>
The six other camels? "The Bayannur's camels could run faster,
but ours are surely smarter," he commented. 
</P>
</TEXT>
