<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 43 Percent of Bangladeshis Below 15 Years Old: UNFPA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Some 43 percent of the
Bangladeshi population are below 15 years old, and, as a result,
the potential for future growth is tremendous, the United Nations
Population Fund (UNFPA) representative in Bangladesh said here on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
At present, Bangladesh has an estimated population of 126
million, UNFPA representative Shuyun Xu told a press conference
at the National Press Club here, adding that the country has
achieved remarkable progress in reducing the population growth
rate from 3 percent in 1973 to 1.6 percent in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Under the most optimistic assumption, Bangladesh's population
would reach 170 million when stabilization of population happens
in 40-45 years' time and if the level for replacement - two
children per couple - is reached by 2005, the UNFPA official said.
</P>
<P>
But a less optimistic and also "a more realistic scenario"
shows that the country's population could reach 200 and 250
million and stabilize around the middle of the next century,
according to Xu.
</P>
<P>
Adolescents aged 10-19 years represent one-fifth of the
country's total population, and the proportion is likely to grow
up to 22 percent during 2000-2005, while the elderly population
will increase from 6 percent in 1995 to 7.7 percent in 2000 and
then 9.1 percent in 2010, he said.
</P>
<P>
Xu said that as the present population programs in the country
are not adequate to meet the requirements of the adolescent and
elderly population, "it is time to reorient policies to meet
adolescent and elderly people's needs."
</P>
<P>
Nearly half of country's population live in poverty and almost
one in every two Bangladeshis is illiterate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990922.0213 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania Urged to Stay in COMESA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government has
appealed to Tanzania to reconsider its decision to pull out of the
Common Market for Eastern and Southern Africa (COMESA).
</P>
<P>
Kenyan High Commissioner Joseph Sefu made this appeal in an
interview in Lusaka Tuesday, saying the decision of withdrawal is
ill-timed, especially at a period when COMESA is in the process of
transforming itself into a regional economic grouping.
</P>
<P>
All other member states are urging Tanzania to remain in the
21-member grouping, Sefu was quoted by Wednesday's Times of Zambia
newspaper as saying.
</P>
<P>
"If Tanzania pulls out, it will be bad because member states
will have to pass through a non-member," he said.
</P>
<P>
Sefu, who is also Chairman of COMESA Council of Ministers, said
no member states had asked to postpone the deadline of zero-tariff
rating from October 31, 2000.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania announced recently that it will withdraw from COMESA
on the ground that given its uncompetitive industrial base, it
will not benefit from the free trade area the grouping will
establish next year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
