<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 07:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon to Issue Eurobonds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon is expected to launch
its new sovereign euro and U.S. dollar bonds worth 750 million
U.S. dollars on either Wednesday or Thursday, the Daily Star
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Underwriters Credit Suisse First Boston and Morgan Stanley
Dean Witter said Monday night the 10-year dollar tranche would be
priced to yield 425-450 basis points over U.S. treasuries, while
the spread on the seven-year euro tranche would be between 37/8
and 41/8 percentage points over French treasuries.
</P>
<P>
"Even if the issue is reduced to 500 million to 600 million
dollars, with pricing of 4 percentage points for the euro and 425
basis points for the dollar, it would still be a very successful
issue," said Joe Sarrouh, senior official at the country's leading
bank Fransabank.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon has sold more than 3 billion eurobonds since 1994,
often at tighter spreads than those achieved by higher-rated
sovereign borrowers.
</P>
<P>
Its 1 billion U.S. dollar eurobond in April 1998 was the
largest sovereign issue ever in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
Spreads on the new eurobond will be wider than current
secondary market yields on the five-year bonds that Lebanon
issued in February worth 200 million dollars and 300 million
euros.
</P>
<P>
Analysts say the wider spreads this time reflect general
market conditions and also Lebanon's desire to attract more
international investments.
</P>
<P>
Its previous sovereign debt issues have been bought largely by
Lebanese banks and other Arab financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investors are expected to subscribe to 25-35 percent
of the issue, compared to about 15 percent of previous eurobonds,
after being courted in recent weeks on a European and North
American roadshow held by the underwriters and Lebanese finance
ministry's officials.
</P>
<P>
The new eurobond is the first issue in a 2 billion foreign
borrowing program approved by Parliament in July and is designed to
reduce the government's reliance on short-term, expensive
Treasury bills.
</P>
<P>
Foreign borrowing only accounts for one quarter of Lebanon's
public debt of almost 20 billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
