<HEADLINE> Ugandan University Okays Army's Imported Food </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
KAMPALA, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Senior food experts from
Uganda's Makerere University have declared the disputed dry ration
recently rejected by the army, fit for human consumption.
</P>
<P>
In a report compiled by the experts, George Nasinyama in
charge of the university food hygiene laboratory, said that there
was no indication of spoilage of the food as well as presence of
pathogenic micro-organisms in the tested food at the time of the
report.
</P>
<P>
He, however, warned that the food should be consumed soon or
it might spoil fast unless kept in better storage conditions of
insect proof, low relative humidity with forced ventilation, the
New Vision daily reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The dry ration, worth some 1.5 million U.S. dollars, comprises
955,000 tins of beans, 955,000 tins of chicken stew and 955,000
sachets of biscuits.
</P>
<P>
It was supplied on credit by Kramer Trade and Technology of
South Africa in June this year.
</P>
<P>
The fresh tests were carried out at the request of the Defense
Ministry following conflicting reports on the quality of the
soldiers' ration issued by a government-appointed pre-shipment
inspection team and government chemists. 
</P>
</TEXT>
