<HEADLINE> UAE Natural Gas Producer Poised to Increase Capacity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Abu Dhabi Gas Liquefaction
Co. (Adgas), the major liquefied natural gas (LNG) producer of the
United Arab Emirates, is making an effort to increase the capacity
of its third LNG plant through a debottlenecking process.
</P>
<P>
"The aim is to seek any bottlenecks in the processing plant for
possible or potential upgrade in output," Fahim Kazem, Adgas
manager for engineering and technical services, was quoted by Gulf
News as saying on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"It is at a study and discussion stage and some options are
under consideration to prove its feasibility," he added.
</P>
<P>
He did not mention what the enhanced capacity of the plant
would be after implementing the debottlenecking process.
</P>
<P>
The current capacity of Adgas' third plant is more than 1.5
million tons per year (tpy).
</P>
<P>
Industry officials said that debottlenecking could raise
output by between 25 to 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Qatar Liquefied Gas Co. (Qatargas) has produced an
additional 1 million tpy of LNG by applying similar technique,
they said.
</P>
<P>
The current total capacity of Adgas, with three plants, is over
4.5 million tpy. It also produces liquefied petroleum gas (LPG)
and sulphur.
</P>
<P>
Since Adgas set up the Middle East's first LNG plant in 1979,
four more grassroot LNG projects have been implemented or are in
the process, Gulf News said.
</P>
<P>
These include Qatargas (with a capacity of 6 million tpy), the
Ras Laffan LNG Co. (5.2 million tpy), Oman LNG Co. (6.6 million
tpy) and the Yemen LNG Co. (5.2 million tpy). 
</P>
</TEXT>
