<HEADLINE> Uganda, Kenya to Disarm Warriors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
KAMPALA, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The governments of Uganda
and Kenya will carry out a joint operation to disarm the armed
warriors in Karamoja and Turkana regions in the two countries
where they rustle each other's cattle.
</P>
<P>
This was revealed by Ugandan Prime Minister Appolo Nsibambi in
response to a report by a parliamentary committee which urged the
government to solve the Karamoja issue completely, the New Vision
paper said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
He said that the government is liaising along with Kenya,
Sudan and Ethiopia within the Inter-governmental Agency on
Development to carry out simultaneous disarmament in this part of
east Africa and to stop further influx of weapons into Karamoja.
</P>
<P>
The government was working hard to coordinate security
intervention in the region characterized by drought, lack of
development and armed conflicts, he added.
</P>
<P>
Warriors in the region rustle cattle from neighboring tribes
and sometimes from neighboring countries. In a recent clash
between two tribes,
</P>
<P>
some 500 people were killed and the figure might shoot up to a
higher level unless military intervention was resorted to in
time.
</P>
<P>
The region reportedly has 8,000 guns, mainly obtained from
arms depot deserted by former armies of the country. The
government has been urged several times to disarm the warriors,
but it did not because the government says that the disarmament
would leave Ugandans there vulnerable to attacks of warriors from
neighboring countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
