<HEADLINE> Dutch Journalist Found Dead in East Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 22 (Xinhua) -- A Dutch journalist named
Sander Thoenes was found dead in Becola village in East Dili,
capital of East Timor, on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
His body was riddled with heavy wounds, according to the Antara
News Agency.
</P>
<P>
International Force for East Timor (Interfet) Commander Maj.
Gen. Peter Cosgrove said Wednesday in Dili that his men were still
examining the location where Thoenes, 30, was found dead.
</P>
<P>
"I have received information on the dead journalist. A team of
Interfet has been sent to the spot to determine if he was really a
journalist," he was quoted by Antara as saying.
</P>
<P>
The Australian commander expressed hope that journalists
covering the situation in East Timor will be careful in doing
their job.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Head of Indonesia's Restoration Operation
Command in East Timor Maj. Gen. Kiki Syahnakri confirmed that a
journalist had died of chopping.
</P>
<P>
Thoenes, who spoke fluent Indonesian, had been a London-based
Financial Times correspondent in Jakarta for the last two years
and also worked for the Dutch weekly Vrij Nederlands.
</P>
<P>
Financial Times said its journalist, arriving in Dili earlier
on Tuesday, had gone missing in Dili later the same day.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that about 100 foreign and domestic journalists
left Dili by a National Defense Force (TNI) Hercules transport
plane on Tuesday afternoon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
