<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Swedish Journalist Injured in U.S.-British Raids </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, September 22 (Xinhua) -- A Swedish journalist was
injured in U.S.-British warplanes' attacks on Iraqi targets on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The journalist, identified as Jan Arell, is part of a Swedish
press delegation that was visiting the historic southern Iraqi
city of Ur, the Iraqi News Agency INA reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Arell, working for the Swedish Gottenburg Post, was
wounded in the chest after being hit by a splinter of a missile
which dropped some meters from the car carrying the press
delegation.
</P>
<P>
After being taken to hospital and treated, Arell sent a story
to his newspaper in Sweden, in which he wrote that he did not find
any military site or see Iraqi anti-aircraft defenses in the area
shelled by the U.S. and British warplanes, said INA.
</P>
<P>
"What has taken place to the Swedish reporter in the city
of Ur is a tangible evidence refuting lies of the U.S. and
British aggressors who claim that they are shelling military
sites and anti-aircraft defenses and they are not targetting
residential areas nor citizens," said INA.
</P>
<P>
Since last December's airstrikes against Iraq, U.S. and
British warplanes have been regularly attacking Iraqi civilian
facilities and military sites, said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The no-fly zones were imposed on Iraq by the U.S.-led
western allies following the 1991 Gulf War with the claimed
aim of protecting the Kurds in the north and the Shiite
Muslims in the south from attacks by Iraqi government troops.
</P>
</TEXT>
