<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN Lawmakers Agree on Peace and Transparency Measures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Lawmakers of the Association
of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) affirmed here Wednesday their
commitment to make the region peaceful, secure and nuclear-free,
despite "threats of conflict from within and outside".
</P>
<P>
In concluding the 20th general assembly of the ASEAN
Inter-Parliamentary Organization (AIPO), the legislators also
approved 19 resolutions concretizing their common concerns.
</P>
<P>
Manuel Villar, Philippine house speaker and the outgoing
president of the AIPO, said "the spirit of ASEAN solidarity and
consensus" as well as "camaraderie" swiftly pave the way for the
approval of those political, social and economical resolutions.
</P>
<P>
The more than 200 delegates from the eight ASEAN member
countries pledged to build up the group as a potent economic force
by supporting the ASEAN Free Trade Area and by making structural
changes to allow transparency in public and private institutions.
</P>
<P>
The AIPO delegates also formalized their concerns about the
moral and social implications of globalization, the impact of
population on ASEAN development, and the need to contain the
spread of crime, drug abuse and AIDS.
</P>
<P>
For the first time since the group's inception, a separate
committee discussed the need to further empower women, especially
in making sure they receive equal access to education and fair
compensation for their labor.
</P>
<P>
The AIPO remains an effective means of dialogue between the
ASEAN members and the observer nations comprising Australia,
China, Japan, Korea, New Zealand, Papua New Guinea and Russia.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Chinese delegate Xu Dunxin gave the
assurance that China will not devalue its currency, although he
added that this assurance cannot be held "forever".
</P>
<P>
During the closing rites of the three-day meeting, Villar
handed the AIPO presidency to Speaker Tan Soo Khoon of Singapore,
host country of the year 2000 general assembly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
