<HEADLINE> TB Cases Rise Seven Times in Southwest Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Tuberculo/AIDS prevalence rate,
a senior Kenyan health official has said.
</P>
<P>
The East African Standard daily Wednesday quoted Kenya's
Director of Medical Service Richard Muga as saying that TB is an
opportunist infection in Nyanza Province and the situation is
worsening.
</P>
<P>
TB infections have risen from 1,192 cases in 1990 to 8,342 in
1998, according to the provincial TB and leprosy treatment
officer Monica Olewe.
</P>
<P>
"TB was already under control in the 1980s but with the
increasing number of HIV/AIDS cases, there has been a steep rise
in TB infections and medical personnel have now intensified
campaigns against the disease," said Muga.
</P>
<P>
Muga urged health officers in the province to provide TB drugs
to all health centers in the region.
</P>
<P>
He also called for all patients suffering form coughs to ensure
early treatment.  
</P>
</TEXT>
