<DOCNO> XIE19990922.0238 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: What Prompts Thailand to Exit IMF? </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Thailand needs no more funds
from the International Monetary Fund (IMF)-sponsored 17.2 billion
U.S. dollar rescue package for the time being, Thai cabinet
decided Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The move, some analysts said, showed that Thailand finally
starts to stand on its own feet.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's boldness came directly from the country's restored
foreign reserves, which have reached a comfortable level of 32.2
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
"That we don't need to borrow further shows our confidence that
our foreign reserves are at a stage appropriate for recovery,"
Finance Minister Tarrin Nimmanhaeminda said Tuesday after a
cabinet meeting.
</P>
<P>
Other economic indicators also point to a recovering economy,
according to the eighth letter of intent to the IMF, which gained
approval of the cabinet Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's economy posted a growth of 3.5 percent from April to
June this year compared with the same quarter last year, the
National Economic and Social Development Board announced earlier
this week.
</P>
<P>
It is the second consecutive quarter which has seen an economic
growth since the second quarter of 1997. In the first quarter this
year, the economy increased 0.8 percent compared with the same
period last year.
</P>
<P>
In the second quarter of this year, the industrial sector
posted the largest gains, growing 7.7 percent year-on-year.
</P>
<P>
The letter of intent, serving as the latest economic review
between the government and the IMF, painted a rosy picture for
Thailand's economy this year by raising its projection of the Thai
economic growth from 1 percent to between 3 and 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
It will be a sharp turnaround from the 10-percent contraction
recorded last year and a fall of 1.8 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Consumer prices have also fallen sharply, with inflation
projected at 0.5 percent for 1999 compared with 8.1 percent in
1998 and 5.6 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The country's foreign reserves, which had depleted to only
about 800 million dollars in August 1997 after a failed baht
defense battle, are expected to stabilize at a targeted level of
32 billion to 34 billion dollars by the end of this year, equal to
7.5 months' export cover and 2.4 times of the country's short-term
external debt.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's current account surplus for 1999 is projected at
11.6 billion dollars, or 9 percent of GDP and overall exports are
expected to reach 55 billion dollars, an increase of 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the strong economic indicators, politics also
played a role in the country's decision of ending fund withdrawal,
some analysts said.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Tarrin and the ruling Democrat Party have long
been criticized for following strictly the IMF prescription and
ignoring the plight of the real economic sectors.
</P>
<P>
Some even said the IMF program made the country sell national
assets at cheap prices to speculative foreigners.
</P>
<P>
The government's decision to detach itself from the IMF at a
time when the general election is expected next year or possibly
later this year is considered by some analysts as a move to woo
more votes.
</P>
<P>
Besides, stopping withdrawals will also ease Thailand's
interest rate payments to the IMF.
</P>
<P>
However, despite its boldness, Thailand is cautious enough to
say it will retain the right of withdrawing funds from the rest
of the package when it feels necessary.
</P>
<P>
"In light of improved outlook, it is not envisaged that further
drawings will be made from the official financing package, unless
the external environment were to deteriorate," the letter of
intent said.
</P>
<P>
The Thai currency, the baht, which traded in a stable narrow
range of 36-38 to the dollar in the first seven months of this
year, has weakened in recent few weeks in line with a highly
volatile yen. It dropped to 40 baht to the dollar last week, the
lowest in 12 months.
</P>
<P>
So far, Thailand has drawn about 13.47 billion dollars from the
bailout package, granted to the country by the IMF in August 1997,
a month after the financial crisis broke out.
</P>
<P>
Finance Ministry officials said the country will still stay in
the IMF economic-reform program and maintain the current fiscal
and monetary policies.
</P>
<P>
Given the 2.65 trillion baht (66.3 billion dollar)
non-performing loans (NPLs) in the banking system, which account
for 47.5 percent of the total outstanding credit, Thailand has the
reason to be cautious.
</P>
<P>
The letter of intent also admitted that progress in
restructuring has been "difficult," hindering the resumption of
normal credit flows.
</P>
<P>
Tarrin also said NPLs had shown signs of improvement in recent
months, but acknowledged that progress has been slow. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
