<HEADLINE> East China Feels Tremors of Taiwan Aftershocks,No Casualties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, September 22 (Xinhua)-- East China's Zhejiang
Province felt strong tremors from several aftershocks of Taiwan's
earthquake. No casualties were reported.
</P>
<P>
According to the Zhejiang Seismological Bureau, shocks of
varying degrees of severity struck some parts of the province at
dawn yesterday, with the cities of Wenzhou, Taizhou and Lishui
hardest hit.
</P>
<P>
The Wenzhou Seismological Station issued a report saying that
at least six aftershocks measuring near five on the Richter Scale
hit the city from the small hours until 6:00 yesterday morning,
but caused no damage or human casualties.
</P>
<P>
But the tremors shook buildings and sent many local residents
into the streets, the report says.
</P>
<P>
The provincial seismological bureau has sent workers to Wenzhou
and other affected areas to inspect the situations there.
</P>
<P>
The aftershocks followed the most powerful earthquake to hit
Taiwan this century, striking the central portion of the island in
the early hours of Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
Latest reports show 1,700 people killed, over 4,000 injured,
nearly 3,000 believed trapped in the rubble, and another 216
missing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
