<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka to Launch New Language Teaching Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka will launch a new
language teaching program from January 2000 in a bid to resolve
conflict among children of different ethnic groups in the war-torn
island country, the Education Ministry said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
A ministry spokesman said that under the program the government
will recruit 6,500 teachers before December this year to teach
Tamil to Sinhala schoolchildren.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Tamil teachers with a knowledge of Sinhala will be
requested to teach Sinhala to Tamil students for which they will
be granted an extra allowance, said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
He said provincial education authorities have been requested to
submit reports giving details of volunteer teachers available.
</P>
<P>
Sinhala and Tamil are two major local languages in Sri Lanka,
spoken respectively by 74 percent and 18 percent of the country's
population.
</P>
<P>
The teaching of the mother language and English will commence
from grade 1 and the teaching of Sinhala and Tamil to other
communities from grade 3, according to the program.
</P>
<P>
The proposal to teach Sinhala to Tamil students and Tamil to
Sinhala students was made by the National Education Commission as
a means of national reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka has been plagued by a 16-year-old war between the
Sinhalese majority-controlled government and Tamil Tiger rebels
who demand a separate homeland for minority Tamils in the north
and east of the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
