<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taiwan Earthquake Leaves 100,000 People Homeless </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The strong earthquake that
rocked Taiwan Tuesday morning has left more than 100,000 Taiwanese
homeless, and rescue work is in full swing, according to media
reports monitored here this morning.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, the powerful earthquake has killed more than 1,700
people, and injured over 4,000, with almost 3,000 believed trapped
in the rubble and another 216 missing, the reports said, quoting
Taiwan's disaster management center.
</P>
<P>
Most deaths are believed to be caused by the collapse of high
buildings, and the damage so far is estimated at some 100 billion
Taiwan dollars (about U.S. dollars 3.2 billion), according to the
reports.
</P>
<P>
The Taiwan Stock Exchange was closed for the second day today
due to power outages, but commercial banks and the foreign
exchange market were set to operate in Taipei.
</P>
<P>
With a population of 2.7 million, Taipei was spared much of the
damage, though the quake destroyed a 12-story hotel in the eastern
part of the city.
</P>
<P>
The quake was Taiwan's deadliest since a 7.4 magnitude tremor
hit the island in 1935, killing 3,276 people.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
