<DOCNO> XIE19990922.0259 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai PM orders Monitoring of Chemical Use, Storage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Thai Prime Minister Chuan
Leekpai has ordered five ministries to adopt a coordinated system
to monitor the use and storage of potentially explosive potassium
chlorate nationwide, the state-run Channel 9 reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Chuan was quoted as saying on Tuesday that the Interior,
Agriculture, Science, Defense and Industry Ministries would
closely monitor the more than 1 million kilograms of potassium
chlorate currently in the hands of 116 private companies allowed
to possess and store the chemical in 29 provinces.
</P>
<P>
The order followed blasts in northern Thailand on Sunday and
it was reported that the number of people killed in the blasts in
a longan processing factory has risen to 35.
</P>
<P>
The 17,000 kilograms of potassium chlorate stored at the
factory is believed to have been the cause of the powerful
explosions, Chuan said. The factory had blown up because it had
not stored the substance correctly, he added.
</P>
<P>
Although potassium chlorate is a controlled substance under
the Military Supplies Act of 1987, the private sector is allowed
to import it. According to the act, importers have to store the
chemical in cool, dry storage sites which must be isolated from
any source of heat or ignition.
</P>
<P>
However, practical enforcement of the act is difficult, the
report noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
