<DOCNO> XIE19990922.0260 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Worldwide IT Workers Demand Exceeds Supply: IDC Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Los Angeles, September 21 (Xinhua) -- The shortage of
information technology (IT) workers currently stands at over one
million worldwide, and the problem will continuously intensify in
the next century, a report released here said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The report released by a U.S. research firm, the International
Data Corporation (IDC), estimated that the shortage of skilled IT
professionals will exceed one million in Europe by 2002, when the
United States will experience intense recruiting for nearly 850,
000 IT employees.
</P>
<P>
"There are no signs that the intense competition for IT staff
will abate, making the 21st century a continuation of the late
1990s, " the report said. "By 2002, the number of openings for IT
workers could represent a number greater than one-fourth of 1998's
total IT workforce."
</P>
<P>
According to IDC, the shortage of IT talent has more to do with
lack of training and company attrition than to a quantitative lack
of qualified people in the IT industry. Companies that spend time
training individuals who do not have the exact technical skills
needed can gain a competitive advantage.
</P>
<P>
Additionally, IDC said, companies that lower their attrition
rates stand to cut their recruiting needs by as much as half. In
fact, attrition management will be the primary focus of human
resources management in the next decade, because the cost of
attrition is often far greater than the cost of recruiting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
