<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar to Build One More Major Bridge Across River </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar is planning to build
one more major bridge across the country's mighty Ayeyawaddy River
at central Mandalay next to the existing Ayeyawaddy River Bridge
at nearby Sagaing which connects Mandalay and Sagaing divisions.
</P>
<P>
The planned construction of the Mandalay Bridge is aimed at
easing the daily traffic jam on the Sagaing Bridge which is a
vital link in the region, said Wednesday's official newspaper The
New Light of Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
The existing Sagaing Bridge was built in 1934.
</P>
<P>
The Myanmar Ministry of Construction is conducting feasibility
study and survey at the appropriate places to build the Mandalay
Bridge, the report said.
</P>
<P>
As Sagaing division was once struck by earthquake in 1956, the
authorities are looking for the possible situation of the faults
in marking the axis to build the bridge and design a modern
earthquake-resistant bridge, the report added.
</P>
<P>
There was only one bridge across Myanmar's Ayeyawaddy River in
the past. After 1988, three other bridges across the river were
built and opened in September 1997 and February and November 1998
respectively.
</P>
<P>
Two more bridges across the Ayeyawaddy River are under
construction and near completion.
</P>
<P>
The Ayeyawaddy River, which flows from north to south for a
distance of about 2,000 kilometers, is known as the rice bowl of
Myanmar with a delta area of some 33,657 square kilometers.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, Myanmar has built 114 bridges
including 12 major ones from 1988 to 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990922.0262 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Romanian President Signs Law to Benefit Medium, Small Enterprises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Romanian medium and small
enterprises will enjoy a package of favorable policies on
approvement procedure, taxation and credit under a new law signed
by President Emil Constantinescu on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
A press communique released by the presidential office said the
law provides a favorable legal frame for establishing and
developing medium-sized enterprises with less than 500 employees
and small-sized enterprises with less than 200 employees.
</P>
<P>
The examining and approving procedure for establishing a medium
or small enterprise will be simplified and must be completed
within 20 days, said the law.
</P>
<P>
Medium and small enterprises have priority in property
purchasing and project and service bidding in the reform of state-
owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The law defines many tax-reduction policies for medium and
small enterprises, such as a tax-free policy for importing
equipment, raw materials and techniques.
</P>
<P>
The Romanian government will set up special foundations to
guarantee loans for medium and small enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Medium and small enterprises will also enjoy priority in
getting information about financial banks, enterprise
administration and market from the national information centers.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that there are more than 600,000 medium and
small enterprises in Romania, most of which are private. Their
production and export value exceed half of the Gross Domestic
Product and the total export revenue of Romania. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
