<HEADLINE> Moderate Earthquake Shakes Guatemala, Part of Mexico </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, September 21 (Xinhua) -- An earthquake of 4.7 on
the Richter scale Tuesday shook the Pacific coast of Guatemala, as
well as neighboring Mexican border area.
</P>
<P>
According to reports from Guatemala, the emergency services
have not got any calls for help, while many people left their
dwellings in panic when the earthquake happened at 8:11 local time
(9:11 in Mexico, 1411 GMT).
</P>
<P>
People in Sierra, Costa and Soconusco of Guatemala and the
Mexican town Tapachula neighboring Guatemala felt the strong quake.
</P>
<P>
The Seismological Institute of Guatemala said that the
earthquake had an intensity of 2 points on the Mercalli scale and
its epicenter was 190 kilometers southeast to the Guatemala city,
off the coast of Escuintla Province.
</P>
<P>
In June, Mexico was shook by two earthquakes of 6.7 and 5.8
degrees on the Richter scale respectively, which caused more than
thirty deaths and disastrous damages, especially on temples of the
16th and 17th century in central Puebla. 
</P>
</TEXT>
