<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Highlights of Major Beijing-Based Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of today's major
Beijing-based newspapers:
</P>
<P>
"People's Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- The toll in the powerful earthquake which struck Taiwan
early Tuesday morning rose to 1,674 dead, with 3,924 injured, 2,
650 trapped and 219 missing till 22:00 Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
The quake, measuring 7.6 on the Richter scale, jolted the
southwestern part of Hualien of Taiwan, 145 kilometers from Taipei,
at 1:47 (Beijing Time) Tuesday morning, followed by at least 13
aftershocks.
</P>
<P>
-- Jiang Zemin, general secretary of Communist Party of China
Central Committee and Chinese president, has extended condolences
to victims of a devastating earthquake that rocked Taiwan at 1:47
am (Beijing Time) Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"We are willing to offer any possible assistance to alleviate
the quake-caused losses," Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
 "Xinhua Daily Telegraph"
</P>
<P>
-- Li Peng, chairman of China's National People's Congress
Standing Committee, said in a meeting Tuesday afternoon with Fred
Gollop, president of the Senate of Barbados, that China values its
ties with Barbados and would like to pursue long-term Sino-
Barbadian friendly and cooperative ties in accordance with the
Five Principles of Peaceful Co-Existence.
</P>
<P>
-- The Red Cross Society of China has pledged to provide
emergency assistance, including 100,000 U.S. dollars in relief
funds and 500,000 yuan worth of relief materials, to Taiwan's
earthquake victims.
</P>
<P>
It also asks its Taiwan counterpart to give further information
about the disaster and assistance needed.
</P>
<P>
 "China Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- The Chinese people will have a three-day National Day
Holiday instead of two according to the regulations on holidays
newly revised by the State Council.
</P>
<P>
According to the revision, people will have three days off on
May 1, International Labor Day, when they used to have one day off;
and they will have one more day off on October 1, National Day.
</P>
