<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Environmental Protection Progressing, Says U.N. Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Under
Secretary General Klaus Topfer described China's changes in the
past two decades as "tremendous, enormous, and remarkable."
</P>
<P>
"I have visited China 12 times in the past 15 years," Topfer
said. "Each time, China gave me a surprise with new buildings
under construction and infrastructure improving."
</P>
<P>
Topfer, also Executive Director of United Nations Environment
Program (UNEP), told Xinhua in an interview here that a world
conference on the protection of the ozone layer will be held in
Beijing in November.
</P>
<P>
In the process of the economic growth, Topfer noted, the
Chinese government is committed to environmental protection and
has made great efforts and invested a lot of money to clean up the
country.
</P>
<P>
"The awareness of environmental protection among Chinese people
has been enhanced greatly in the past years," Topfer stressed.
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese government has also conducted open, good and
friendly cooperation with UNEP," Topfer said.
</P>
<P>
On China's housing issues, Topfer, who is also acting executive
director of the U.N. Center for Human Settlements (Habitat), said
the ongoing reform on China's housing policy is a good thing.
</P>
<P>
"With the introduction of market elements into housing issue,
people are stimulated to save more money and more flats will be
built, the thorny problem of housing will be solved gradually," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Topfer also noted that China is an active partner in the global
Sustainable Cities Program (SCP), a joint program sponsored by the
Habitat and UNEP since 1996.
</P>
<P>
Shenyang and Wuhan, two big industrialized cities in China,
have implemented the program, which helps municipal authorities to
work with non-governmental organizations, private sectors and the
community in an effort to improve urban environment planning and
management capacities, he noted
</P>
<P>
"I am proud that the Mayor of Shenyang, Mu Suixin, received the
Habitat Scroll of Honor in 1998" for his leadership in taking the
city back from pollution. And this year's World Habitat Day will
be held on October 4 in Dalian and its mayor Bo Xilai will be
awarded the 1999 Habitat Scroll of Honor for his outstanding
contribution to housing improvement and sustainable urban
development in Dalian, Topfer said.
</P>
<P>
As part of the celebrations for the World Habitat Day, Shenyang
and Wuhan will make presentations at the International Forum on
Cities for All in a bid to encourage other cities to adopt similar
strategies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
