<HEADLINE> Pak Files Case Against India for Downing of Aircraft </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan Tuesday formally
filed a case in the International Court of Justice at The Hague,
seeking reparations from New Delhi for India's shooting down of an
unarmed Pakistani naval aircraft in August.
</P>
<P>
"The government of Pakistan has filed a case in the ICJ, with a
view to securing the court's judgment that India is under an
obligation to make reparations to Pakistan for the loss of the
aircraft and compensation to the heirs of those killed as a result
of the breaches of obligations assumed by it under the Charter of
the United Nations and the relevant rules of customary
International Law and Treaty provisions," the Pakistani Foreign
Office said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
On August 10, Indian Air Force jets fired air-to-air missiles
on an unarmed Atlantique aircraft of the Pakistan Navy on a
training mission. All 16 personnel on board were killed.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan has formally demanded from India an amount of 60.2
million U.S. dollars as compensation for the loss of the aircraft
and for the loss of lives of the personnel on board. 
</P>
</TEXT>
