<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "La Nina" Hits Coast of Ecuador </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QUITO, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Cold and drought, caused by "La
Nina", are hitting the coast of Ecuador, affecting agriculture and
people's health.
</P>
<P>
According to a report by the Oceanographic Institute of the
Ecuadorian Navy published on Tuesday, the low temperatures in the
coastal areas have caused the flowering crops to lose their
flowers, thereby lowering the quantity of fruit.
</P>
<P>
The climactic anomaly has also lowered the yield of other
agricultural products such as corn, soya and melon.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the cold has increased the presence of respiratory
illnesses such as colds, coughs, bronchitis and pneumonia.
</P>
<P>
However, the cold has obviously increased the catch of fishes
such as tuna, red snapper, catfish, albacore, corvina, shark,
various kinds of shellfish, but decreased the catch of marine
shrimps.
</P>
<P>
According to information obtained from the permanent monitoring,
the evolution of the cold spell makes it possible to confirm the
presence of the phenomenon of "La Nina" which may extend to the
early months of the year 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990922.0291 </DOCNO>
