<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Illiteracy Stands at 6 Million </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 22 (Xinhua) -- There are 6.07 million
illiterate Indonesians between the ages of 10 and 44, The Jakarta
Post Wednesday quoted an official as saying.
</P>
<P>
The director of non-formal schooling at the Ministry of
Education and Culture Endro Sumardjo said he hoped these people
could become literate by the year 2004 through intensive courses.
</P>
<P>
The ministry earlier stated that its goal was to bring this
number below 5 million by 1999, but the economic crisis made this
target impossible to reach, he said.
</P>
<P>
There were 6.9 million illiterate Indonesians in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Endro, however, expressed optimism that intensive language
courses could reduce illiteracy by 1 million people per year.
</P>
<P>
In cooperation with local administrations, the ministry also
sponsors continuing education for those who have recently become
literate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
