<HEADLINE> EU Urges Indonesia to Withdraw Troops from East Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HELSINKI, September 21 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU)
Urged on Tuesday Indonesia to pull out its military forces from
East Timor and welcomed the progress in the deployment of
International Force there.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued by Finland, EU present rotating
presidency, the 15-nation bloc asked the Indonesian government to
withdraw its armed forces from East Timor completely and at an
early date and to rapidly contain and disarm all paramilitary
elements in the territory.
</P>
<P>
EU applauded the progress in disposing international troops in
East Timor, pledging to continue to support the work of the UN
Secretary General Kofi Annan and the United Nations Mission there
in pursuing the consultation process towards the independence of
the province.
</P>
<P>
In the statement, EU paid tribute to those Asian countries, the
ASEAN states in particular, which have contributed to the
establishment of the international force.
</P>
<P>
The group also expressed grave concern over the humanitarian
situation in East and West Timor. It repeated its earlier appeals
for allowing immediate safe access for international humanitarian
organizations to both East and West Timor.
</P>
<P>
The statement said EU supported calls for forming an
international Commission of Inquiry to investigate cases in which
international humanitarian law has allegedly been violated.
</P>
</TEXT>
