<HEADLINE> Timberwolves Forward Smith Breaks Foot </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Minnesota Timberwolves
forward Joe Smith could miss the start of the season after
undergoing surgery today to repair a broken bone in his left food.
</P>
<P>
The procedure was performed at the Minneapolis Sports Medicine
Center by team orthopedic surgeon Dr. David Fischer, who placed a
screw in the fifth metatarsal bone.
</P>
<P>
The top overall pick in the 1995 draft, Smith broke his foot in
a pick-up game at UCLA on Thursday. This summer, he re-signed with
the Timberwolves, inking a one-year, $2.2 million deal.
</P>
<P>
Training camp opens in early October and the 1999-2000 season
begins November 2. Smith's foot will be in a cast for one week and
he is expected to return in six to seven weeks.
</P>
<P>
"We are disappointed that this happened to Joe after he worked
so hard this summer," We are disappointed that this happened to
Joe after he worked so hard this summer," Wolves coach and general
manager Flip Saunders said. "We are encouraged that the surgery
was a success and that he will be back around the time we start
the regular season."
</P>
<P>
Smith, 24, averaged 13.7 points and 8.2 rebounds last season,
his first with the Timberwolves. He teamed with superstar Kevin
Garnett at forward and helped Minnesota reach the postseason for
the third straight year.
</P>
<P>
Drafted by the Golden State Warriors, Smith averaged 15.3
points as a rookie and a career-high 18.7 points in the 1996-97
season. However he demanded a lucrative long-term deal and the
Warriors dealt him to the Philadelphia 76ers, who allowed him to
depart as a free agent following the 1997-98 season. 
</P>
