<HEADLINE> Italy to Intensify Fighting Against Crimes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Italian Prime Minister Massimo D
'Alema announced Tuesday evening that the government intended to
put more money and manpower into fighting against violent crime.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after discussing an anti-crime package with his
cabinet, D'Alema also promised that authorities would soon begin
testing new security ideas such as an electronic bracelet for
convicted criminals on parole.
</P>
<P>
"The government is committed to improving the state's response
to crime through organizational changes," he said.
</P>
<P>
D'Alema said 500 billion lire (about 270 million U.S. dollars)
would be made available for extra police work and a further 6,000
law enforcement officers would be put onto Italy's streets.
</P>
<P>
The Italian government is scheduled to meet regional prefects
and local police chiefs next Monday in order to discuss the
measures it intends to take to confront crime.
</P>
<P>
In April, after a series of killings in the Italian northern
city of Milan, the government came up with a draft law stiffening
penalties for violent crimes and giving police more powers to
pursue criminals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
