<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Argentina Urges dialogue with Britain on Island Dispute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Argentina said Tuesday
circumstances became ripe for a dialogue with Britain on a
definitive solution of the Malvinas (Falkland) Islands dispute.
</P>
<P>
"I am convinced that circumstances are now conducive for
Argentina and the United Kingdom to start without further delay"
such a dialogue, President Carlos Saul Menem told the 54th Session
of the U.N. General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
He said the reestablishment of diplomatic relations between the
two countries in February 1990 opened a new stage for the creation
of bilateral ties at the highest level in history.
</P>
<P>
The event took place eight years after British troops occupied
the islands.
</P>
<P>
Menem said Argentina, "reaffirming its sovereignty rights and
urged by a spirit of reconciliation", has harmoniously worked with
Britain on different fields related to the South Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
They include the rebuilding of a climate of mutual trust in
the area, the preservation of live marine resources, the
exploration and exploitation of hydrocarbons, the reestablishment
of flights between the continent and the Malvinas islands.
</P>
<P>
The President said Argentina's constitution "establishes as a
national goal the recovery of the Malvinas Islands and guarantees
that the way of life of their inhabitants will be strictly
respected". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990922.0311 </DOCNO>
