<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Popularity of Light Trucks A Trend in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, September 21 (Xinhua) -- If the market share of
light trucks was to maintain its growth rate of the past decade in
the United States, more than two in three new vehicles sold by
2010 would be trucks, said a market analysis report released
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
For years, the family car in the United States was a sedan or a
station wagon. Now the family car is a truck, according to the
report from the Polk Company, a market analysis firm.
</P>
<P>
In 1970, U.S. automotive sales were comprised approximately 85
percent cars and 15 percent light trucks, Polk said. With the
popularity of the minivan in the 1980s, followed by the sport
utility vehicle in the 1990, several manufacturers now sell
primarily trucks. DaimlerChrysler, for example sold two trucks for
each car last year, while Ford and General Motors sold about 60
percent and 46 percent light trucks, respectively, in 1998. In
total, 47 percent of all vehicle sales last year were trucks.
</P>
<P>
Economic factors such as rising income and low fuel prices have
contributed to the popularity of trucks, according to Polk.
</P>
<P>
Lifestyle changes can also influence vehicle choice. The growth
of edge cities and remote suburbs put the modern family in more
rugged terrain for housing and hobbies, and the roads are a
challenge for small vehicles.
</P>
<P>
Another trend influencing the popularity of trucks is the
growth of multiple-vehicle households in the United States. The
number of people in a household remaining stable, combined with a
strong economy, has enabled the number of vehicles per household
in the United States to grow from 1.2 in 1960 to 1.9 in 1998. As a
nation, Polk said, the United States has moved from households
owning one car to households owning one car and one truck. This
increase in ownership translates into the sales figure to nearly
15 million vehicles that has occurred in the last five years.
</P>
<P>
The average family is likely to choose a car if they can only
own one vehicle, Polk predicted. However, there are increased
preferences for trucks when adding another vehicle. The attraction
may be the extra space for carrying passengers or cargo. The
average truck is also larger, more powerful and safer than the
average car.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
