<HEADLINE> Tropical Storm Harvey Reaches Southern Florida </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Tropical Storm Harvey
reached southern Florida Tuesday with 50 mph winds, bringing heavy
rain, street flooding and tornada warnings.
</P>
<P>
Florida Governor Jeb Bush declared a state of emergency for 56
of 67 counties as the storm approached and schools closed in some
areas such as Tampa, Orlando and the Florida Keys, but no
significant damage was reported.
</P>
<P>
The storm, formed in the Gulf of Mexico, was expected to hit
near Tampa in central Florida. But a cold front pushed it
southward and it sliced across the southern tip of the Florida
peninsula toward the Atlantic Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The storm, which could produce storm surge flooding of up to 6
feet above normal in some places, was expected to cross Florida
and stay offshore as it heads north along the East Coast.
</P>
<P>
Five to 10 inches of rain were expected from the storm
forecast to come ashore near Naples, 150 miles south of
Clearwater, by Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
"Essentially, the southern peninsula of Florida is going to
get lots of rain and gust," said Stephen Baig, oceangrapher at
the National Hurricane Center in Miami.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
