<HEADLINE> Mozambique to Launch Prawn Breeding Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Mozambican fishing company
Quelimar has raised about 31 million US dollars to launch a
project for breeding prawns in the country's northern coast
province of Nampula by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
The Quelimar manager, Martinho Xavier Cossa, said the company
has recently completed the assessment.
</P>
<P>
A source in the National Fisheries Directorate said that the
Mozambican government has defined the breeding of prawns as a
priority for development of the fishing sector.
</P>
<P>
Mozambique's potential for the fishing of prawns on the open
seas is currently estimated at about 7,000 tonnes a year, with
170,000 hectares suitable for such business.
</P>
<P>
According to a study conducted by the National Fisheries
Directorate, the Mozambican coast is home to the white, tiger, and
brown tiger prawns.
</P>
<P>
Prawns represent about 40 percent of the total value of
Mozambique's exports. Currently prawns earn the country about 80
million U.S. dollars a year, compared with 34 million dollars in
1986.  
</P>
</TEXT>
