<HEADLINE> Mercosur to Present Posture on Terrorism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, September 21 (Xinhua) -- The interior ministries
of the countries of the Common Market of the South (Mercosur) plus
Chile and Bolivia discussed here Tuesday a common position on
terrorism.
</P>
<P>
The South American initiative will be presented during an
anti-terrorism meeting to be held in Miami on September 28 and 29.
</P>
<P>
Mercosur is made up of Argentina, Brazil, Paraguay and Uruguay,
with Chile and Bolivia as associate members.
</P>
<P>
The sponsor of the meeting, the Inter-American Commission for
the Fight Against Terrorism, was created during the assembly of the
Organization of American States (OAS), held this year in
Guatamala.
</P>
<P>
Argentine Interior Minister Carlos Corach said he trusted the
commission against terrorism to guarantee the security and
democracy of the nations of the American continent.
</P>
<P>
He expressed confidence that work carried out by the commission
would not interfere with internal matters of the member countries.
</P>
<P>
One of the agreed points was the creation of an information
bank, to which the 34 OAS member countries will have access, said
Corach.
</P>
<P>
Cuba has not been a member of the OAS since 1962. 
</P>
</TEXT>
