<HEADLINE> Reporters Without Frontiers Gives Warning Over Colombia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, September 21 (Xinhua) -- The international
organization Reporters Without Frontiers said Tuesday that
Colombia was the most dangerous country for the press in Latin
America.
</P>
<P>
In a letter sent to Colombian Attorney General Alfonso Gomez,
Reporters Without Frontiers lamented the deaths by the bullet of
Colombian reporter Guzman Quintero last Thursday and of Jaime
Garzon on August 13, in addition to anonymous threats made to a
further 10 professionals in the field.
</P>
<P>
The letter was signed by the general secretary of Reporters
Without Frontiers, Robert Menard.
</P>
<P>
The group, with its headquarters in Paris, warned the Colombian
government to provide as soon as possible a protection program for
reporters in the South American country.
</P>
<P>
The organization also recalled the death, in July of 1998, of
the reporter Luz Amparo Jimenez, who had received threats from
anti-rebel paramilitary groups.
</P>
<P>
According to the organization, the majority of Colombian
reporters have received death threats.
</P>
<P>
The assassinated reporter Guzman Quintero, aged 35, was the
editorial chief of the newspaper El Pilon and was killed in the
bar of a hotel in Valledupar, capital of the northern province of
Cesar.
</P>
<P>
Garzon, humorist and reporter on both radio and television, who
was promoting contact between the guerrilla movement and the
government, was shot in Santafe de Bogota. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
