<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Calls for Security Council Attention to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 21 (Xinhua) -- China Tuesday called
upon the U.N. Security Council to increase its input in the
African issue, and make concrete action in coordinating and
cooperating with the efforts to the end by African countries and
regional groups.
</P>
<P>
The statement came as Qin Huasun, Chinese permanent
representative to the United Nations, took the floor at the
Security Council, which met in an open session to discuss the
situation of Africa.
</P>
<P>
"We hold that the United Nations and the international
community should pay more attention to the question of Congo (K),"
he said.
</P>
<P>
"Congo (K) is considered 'the heart of Africa', the conflict in
that country not only affects the Great Lake region, but also
affects the peace and stability on the continent of Africa as a
whole," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The signing of the Lusaka accord marks the beginning of the
peace process in the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC)," he said.
"But the full implementation is a difficult process, it needs the
active participation of the international community and the United
Nations."
</P>
<P>
"It is our view that if the international community and the
United Nations, at the current stage, fail to invest necessary
material and manpower, the root course of the conflict can not be
addressed," he said. "The crisis would break out again, and we
would have to pay a higher, or even more tragic price."
</P>
<P>
"China has always attached importance to the question of
Africa, and we always supported the just demands and the
reasonable proposals by African countries," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We endorse the idea that African countries should make their
own efforts to maintain political stability and promote economic
development, and we always supported the African efforts in
strengthening their unity and regional cooperation," he said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier at the meeting, Zambian President Frederick Chiluba,
who led the mediation efforts, briefed the Council on the
ceasefire accord in the Democratic Republic of Congo.
</P>
<P>
"China highly appreciated what has been done by President
Chiluba and his contribution to the question of DRC," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
