<HEADLINE> Bush Breaks 50 Million Dollars Barrier in Fund Raising </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 21 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Republican
presidential front-runner George W. Bush has broken the 50 million
dollars barrier by raising more than 52 million dollars so far for
the 2000 presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
His advisers said earlier this month that they expected
the Texas governor to beat the 50 million dollars mark by the end
of September.
</P>
<P>
Bush is requested to report his finance situation in fund
raising from the period of July 1 through September 30 to the
Federal Election Commission on October 15.
</P>
<P>
At the end of June, Bush had raised 37 million dollars and had
30 million dollars in the bank.
</P>
<P>
Bush's 52 million dollars is more money than any other
presidential candidate ever has had to spend on a campaign, even
including federal matching funds.
</P>
<P>
Including the federal funds, 1996 Republican presidential
nominee Bob Dole had 45 million dollars to spend and President
Clinton had 43 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Bush said that he would not accept federal funding, which would
require his campaign to limit its spending to around 40 million
dollars in the primaries.
</P>
<P>
By refusing the federal assistance, Bush can spend as much as
he can raise, allowing him to financially compete with publisher
Steve Forbes, who also is not accepting federal funds for his
largely self-financed campaign.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
