<HEADLINE> Wall Street Stocks Fall Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
NEW YORK, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Wall Street stocks fell
sharply Tuesday because of the weakening dollar, the growing
U.S. trade deficit and the lower-than-expected earnings warning.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average closed down 225.43, or 2
percent at 10,598.47. The blue chip index fell as much as 272.03
during the trading.
</P>
<P>
Broader stock indicators were also lower. The Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 index fell 27.95 at 1,307.58 and the technology heavy
Nasdaq composite index fell 65.05 at 2,821.10.
</P>
<P>
The market plunged as the dollar continued to slide to 104.87
today from 106.38 Monday against the Japanese yen in New York,
which, investors feared, would prompt the Federal Reserve to raise
interest rates for the third time this year to fight inflation
because a weaker dollar can be inflationary.
</P>
<P>
A government report on high trade deficit also helped to
push the stock lower. The report said the U.S. trade deficit
rose to a monthly record of 25.2 billion U.S. dollars in July,
disappointing investors.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Apple Computer announced late Monday that its
earnings for the third quarter would be hurt by a shortage of
chips. The announcement discouraged investors.
</P>
<P>
The earthquake in the Taiwan region also led a range of
semiconductor stocks to fall.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE index fell 11.11 at 600.99 and the American Stock
Exchange index fell 7.87 at 784.98. The Russell 2000 index of
smaller companies fell 6.70 at 426.50.
</P>
<P>
Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 10-to-3 margin
on the New York Stock Exchange, with 2,362 down, 697 up and 492
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume increased to 785.33 million shares from 564.95
million in the previous session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
